[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

{ Welcome to the Beginner’s 1.e4 e5 repertoire!  Just like my first two beginner courses, this course too offers a comprehensive repertoire but does so without overloading you with an excessive number of opening variations as a lifetime repertoire might.    As it has become my modus operandi in my repertoire courses. I will be teaching you an entire repertoire as well as developing and reinforcing sound chess habits and principles - covered extensively in my 'CPR' courses.  As a result, your learning will be twofold: first, you will master ambitious opening variations. Second, you will develop a better understanding of their resulting middlegame scenarios.  The Beginner's 1.e4 e5 builds upon a healthy mix of aggressive attacking systems and positional variations. This mix was a conscious choice by me in order to maximize your growth as a chess player in every aspect of the game.  At the conclusion of each chapter the course features an excellent selection of model games, which have been chosen to demonstrate the application of the discussed lines. This structured approach will enable you to cement your grasp of each chapter's lines - and their underlying concepts - as you work your way through the course.  The lines and ideas offered in this course have been carefully selected based on my 20 years of coaching experience as well as extensive testing both online and over the board. The quality of the chosen lines and the depth of the analysis means that, notwithstanding its title, you can continue to draw upon the depth of the course’s ideas all the way up to FIDE 2000.  Once again, I would like to extend my greatest gratitude to my student, Lukas Opacic, whose help proved to be invaluable, both chess-wise and otherwise! }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "King's Gambit"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5
{ The King's Gambit is an enduring legacy of the romantic era.   This opening is particularly popular on club level as it is an aggressive attacking opening with plenty of tactical potential.   However, when countered correctly, Black faces absolutely no problems at all. }
2. f4 d5
{ This move technically introduces the Falkbeer Countergambit, however, in our case it is going to be simply a move-order trick to return to the main lines, avoiding some sidelines along the way. }
3. exd5 { 3.Nf3  exf4  transposes into the main line after a few more moves. }
3... exf4
{ And thus, we are back in the main lines of the King's Gambit,  3...e4  would be the Falkbeer countergambit. }
4. Nf3
{ Without a doubt the best move for White as virtually everything else allows Qh4+. }
4... Nf6 5. c4 c6
{ This move is very important! We eliminate the d5-pawn in order to accelerate development of the b8-Knight. }
6. d4 cxd5 7. Bxf4 Bb4+
{ This check comes in handy as it allows us to quickly castle. In contrast, White's King feels rather nervous on the open e-file. }
8. Nc3 O-O 9. Be2 dxc4
{ We make the Bishop move again, thus exposing the King! } 10. Bxc4 Qe7+
{ This is the better check as it allows us a neat tactical resource: } 11. Ne5
Nc6
{ And Black is clearly better due to the fact that  12.O-O  can't be played without losing material,  12...Nxd4!  13.Qxd4  Bc5 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Danish Gambit"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4 3. c3
{ The Danish Gambit is one of the most notable examples of the Romantic chess style, stemming from the mid-1800s.   The idea, as is very common with most gambits, is to sacrifice a pawn or two in order to accelerate White's development and obtain superior central control.   This opening, just like many other early gambits is rarely seen on a professional level as they allow Black to equalize very easily @@StartBracket@@often even get the upper hand!@@EndBracket@@. }
3... d5
{ This central counter-punch is going to be our key idea to combat the gambit. }
4. exd5 Nf6
{ This is a major detour from the well-known  4...Qxd5  , which leads to a very dry and equal endgame.  The text aims to recapture on d5 with the Knight, a far more optimal scenario, as we have learned from Grandpa Nimzowitsch that the Knight is the ultimate blockader! }
5. c4 { This greedy move gets punished quickly: } 5... Bb4+ 6. Bd2 Bxd2+ 7.
Nxd2 O-O 8. Bd3 c6
{ And Black takes over the initiative. Re8 is coming and White's minor pieces are very passively placed. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Bishop's Opening"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4 { This move aptly introduces the 'Bishop's Opening'. } 2... Nf6
{ This is best and is also in sync with our other lines. After  3.Nc3  Nxe4  we transpose to our Vienna lines, which we will examine in the main course. }
3. d3
{ This is by far the most played move here. White often transposes into other openings such as the Vienna and the Italian, and sometimes even King's Gambit lines with f4.   Our main move denies all transitions and dictates the character of the game. }
3... c6
{ Utilizing the fact that White exerts no pressure on the e5 pawn, Black ambitiously aims to execute the d7-d5 break very early on. }
4. Nf3 d5 5. Bb3
{ White should delay the capture on d5 as it denies Black playing Nc6. } 5...
Bd6 6. Nc3
{ The best and most popular move. White is trying to provoke a d5-d4 push, which would allow the b3-Bishop to fully come to life.   Also, the Ne2-g3 maneuver is something White is keen to do anyway! }
6... h6
{ It is not very often that I attach an exclam to the 'bunny ears', so enjoy the moment while you can!  The idea is that d5 is actually rather risky to capture and so Black uses this time to deny White the annoying Bg5 pin.  Note that on Super GM level  6...dxe4  has been preferred, but to be perfectly honest, the capture makes more sense to me once Ng5 has been denied. }
7. O-O dxe4
{ This move is a bit of a @@StartBracket@@sad@@EndBracket@@ necessity here.   Due to the lost tempo on the h6 move, Be6 is no longer playable as White can blast open the center with the energetic d3-d4!   On the other hand, h6 also denies White's Ng5-Nxe4 maneuver, so we can't complain. }
8. Nxe4 Nxe4 9. dxe4 Qf6
{ This is a cool idea: The Queen covers the d6 Bishop and allows the Knight to develop via d7. }
10. Be3 O-O
{ With an even position. Black looks to play Nd7-c5 with a comfortable game.   Please note that in this position I don't recommend the plan of Bg4 and then taking on f3, as it favors White. This is because the Bishop pair is more important than the slightly compromised pawn formation. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Vienna"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nc3
{ This move introduces the Vienna game. The most common idea behind the setup is to play a 'delayed King's Gambit'. }
2... Nf6
{ 2...Nc6  is also known here but the text is the most challenging. Black is preparing the d7-d5 counterpunch. }
3. f4 d5
{ With this move we echo our setup vs the King's Gambit. The idea is identical: immediately counterpunching in the center. }
4. fxe5 Nxe4 5. Nf3 Bc5
{ This move seems counterintuitive as it induces d2-d4. The benefit of doing so is that this way we get to retain the Knight on e4!   The other main line goes with Be7 when White kicks the e4 Knight with d3. }
6. d4 Bb4 7. Bd2 c5
{ It is important to play this move before Nc6, so we can pressure the center with all our might! }
8. Bb5+ { This is also often played here. } 8... Nc6 9. O-O O-O
{ Black's very active pieces and central pressure already secure an advantage. }
10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. Nxe4
{ This move leads to masses of trades similar to the main line. } 11... dxe4
12. Bxb4 cxb4 13. Ne1 Ba6
{ The Bishop stands very well here, White might even get in trouble on the f-file! }
14. Rf4 f5 15. exf6 Rxf6
{ And White is in trouble.   Our Bishop is far superior to the Knight and the e4 passer combined with the f-file threats guarantee a sizeable edge for Black! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Four Knights Scotch"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4
{ This move introduces the Four Knights Scotch, whereas  4.Bb5  is the Four Knights Spanish. }
4... exd4 5. Nxd4 Bb4
{ Black immediately begins the fight for the center, e4 is now hanging. } 6.
Nxc6 bxc6 7. Bd3 d5
{ Black immediately challenges the center and sets about utilizing the doubled c-pawns. }
8. exd5 O-O
{ Along with  8...cxd5  this is the other main line.  I chose this variation as  8...cxd5  exclusively leads to dull and structurally slightly inferior positions. In contrast, the text allows White far more opportunities to make a mistake. }
9. O-O Bg4
{ We insist on rapid development at the cost of delaying the recapture. } 10.
f3 Bh5 11. dxc6
{ Although White is two pawns up, this is completely fine as we are now ready to launch our counterattack! }
11... Qd4+ 12. Kh1 Bxc3 13. bxc3 Qxc3
{ The good news is that we are recuperating all the lost material without any drama.   The not-so-good news is that, as is typical in the Scotch Four Knights, the resulting position is not exactly thrilling... }
14. Bf4 Qxc6
{ And Black has comfortably equalized.   A further plan is to trade a pair of Bishops with Bg6 and then bring the rooks into the game with Rfe8 and Rad8. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Four Knights Spanish"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5
{ This move is the Four Knights Spanish, a variation that is played very rarely on club level. }
4... Nd4
{ I chose this move because, contrary to the other main line with Bb4, it allows Black many fun and exciting positions. }
5. Bc4 Bc5
{ These sacrificial ideas are common in the Nd4 variation, which is precisely why I picked it.   In general, the idea is to let go of the e5 pawn and use the tempi White spends on capturing it to create an attack. }
6. Nxe5 { 6.O-O  avoids confrontations but also promises little for White. }
6... Qe7
{ Another pawn sac, but White can't accept it without risking a spectacular loss. }
7. Nd3 d5
{ This is a must and is in fact a common motif in this opening. Black must strike while the iron is hot. }
8. Nxd5 Qxe4+ 9. Ne3 Bd6
{ This is the right diagonal as we want to be able to attack the h2 pawn once White has castled. }
10. O-O b5 11. Bb3 O-O
{ And Black has sensational compensation for the pawn.   Our plan is to play Qh4 next, provoking g3, and then attack the light color complex with Qh3, Bg4, etc. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Ponziani"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3
{ This funky-looking move introduces the Ponziani.   White's idea is to conquer the center with d2-d4, which, of course, we are not going idly allow... }
3... d5
{ This is the most thematic central countermeasure. Black strikes in the center before White can get d4 in.   Note that c3 will turn out to be a rather ugly move in many variations, as it will greatly hinder White's development of the queenside. }
4. Qa4 Bd7
{ Although f6 is the preferred method of the top GMs, such an ugly move can't be recommended in a course that prides itself on its sound principles 😊. }
5. exd5 Nd4
{ With this move we send the White Queen on another excursion, allowing us to pull ahead in development. }
6. Qd1 Nxf3+ 7. Qxf3 Nf6
{ Morphy would be rubbing his hands in glee! White has nothing developed and the c3 pawn adds insult to injury. }
8. c4 { This is an attempt to revive the b1-Knight as soon as possible. } 8...
Bc5 9. Nc3 c6
{ Black needs to 'bite' into the central pawns in order to initiate a fight before White completes development. }
10. h3
{ White needs to eliminate the Bg4 threat before playing Be2.   To be fully honest, I find it insulting that Black here does not have a decisive lead, but sometimes the engines prove the ugliest moves the most resilient. }
10... O-O 11. Be2 cxd5 12. cxd5 Ne8
{ Speaking of not-so-aesthetic moves, this retreat seems to be the best to fight for an edge.   The idea is that in order to recover d5, Black would have to give up the Bishop @@StartBracket@@Bb4-Bxc3@@EndBracket@@.   Instead, we opt to reroute the Knight to the delicious d4 outpost and leave the doubled d-pawns alone. }
13. O-O Nd6 14. d3 Nf5
{ And Black has a preferable position.   Once the Knight lands on d4, we can launch the second wave of the attack with f7-f5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez Schliemann"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 f5
{ The Schliemann @@StartBracket@@also known as Jaenisch@@EndBracket@@ Gambit is a bold choice to contest one of the most classical and respected chess openings.   Apart from the fact that this line is sharp and confrontational, it also allows players to reduce their workload by eliminating a large number of side variations, such as the Exchange Spanish, the early d4-lines, and the early d3-variations, etc. }
4. Nc3 fxe4 5. Nxe4 Nf6 6. Qe2 d5 7. Nxf6+ gxf6
{ 7...Qxf6?  is not a good way to sac a pawn, because of  8.Qxe5+ } 8. d4 Bg7
{ This is the right way to sac!   Once again, our priority is piece activity and initiative! }
9. dxe5 O-O 10. exf6 Qxf6 11. O-O Bg4 { And Black is already ahead! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Scotch Game"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ This ambitious central break introduces the Scotch Game. } 3... exd4 4. Nxd4
Nf6
{ This alongside  4...Bc5  is the most thematic response. Black immediately challenges the e4-pawn. }
5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7
{ This is the main move in this position. Black's goal is to lure the white Queen to e2, creating a unique situation where both sides struggle to develop their Bishops. }
7. Qe2 Nd5 8. c4 Ba6
{ This move allows us to keep the Knight on d5, due to the pin, and it also prepares queenside castling. }
9. b3
{ This move makes our Bishop on a6 look a bit silly, but remember that we can always reactivate this piece with Bb7 and then c6-c5! }
9... O-O-O 10. Bb2 Qg5
{ This is a very ambitious move, which I recommend instead of the more theoretical f6. }
11. Nd2 { This and g3 are roughly of same value. } 11... Qg6
{ We are aiming to cause trouble on c2, so White must react. } 12. Rc1 Bb4
{ Once again, we have reached a position where we have completed development and White is still quite far away from castling!   Principled, sound chess is always what we should aim for! We have ideas such as d7-d6 break followed by Rhe8 and even Nf4 is still a real threat. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Two Knights"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6
{ Note that we will transpose after  4.d4  , and we've examined that already in the Scotch Gambit chapter. }
4. Ng5
{ This move steers the game towards the variation known as the Fried Liver, just to add another example to the list of openings that were not exactly named with too much thought in mind... }
4... d5 { This is Black's only way to shield the f7 pawn. } 5. exd5 b5
{ This is a cheeky, daring, and most importantly, fun variation.   The idea is to sacrifice a pawn in order to pull ahead in development and central control, a common goal in many of our lines.   Lately, the biggest main line with Na5 has grown immensely, and its theory has become both very deep and dense so I thought it best to avoid it. }
6. Bf1 Nxd5
{ This move introduces our main idea.   The line has long been known but we hope to turn around some of the old@@StartBracket@@er@@EndBracket@@ evaluations! }
7. Bxb5 Bb7 8. d4
{ White's most ambitious and aggressive move, that defends the Knight on g5 and challenges the center at the same time.   Now the game becomes very sharp and any mistake may be the last one for both sides! }
8... exd4 9. O-O Be7 10. Re1 O-O 11. Nf3 a6
{ We are provoking White to grab the pawn on d4 at the cost of giving up the Bishop! }
12. Bf1 Bc5
{ And Black stands perfectly well with superior central control and development.  Note that White's most logical  13.Nbd2  is very strongly met by  13...Ne3!! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Scotch Gambit"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d4
{ This move steers the game to the Scotch Gambit. } 4... exd4 5. O-O
{ This move offers another pawn. At first sight, it may look dangerous to accept, but in reality the disappearance of the white center reduces White's attacking potential. }
5... Nxe4 6. Re1 d5 { This move ensures that White can't win a piece on e4. }
7. Bxd5
{ White's only move to keep the attack going and to recover one of the sacrificed pawns. }
7... Qxd5 8. Nc3 Qh5
{ The other big theoretical line is Qa5, but the text leads to easier positions for Black. }
9. Nxe4 Be6
{ This developing move is very handy as it also shields the King from the discovered checks. }
10. Neg5
{ This move regains the material for White, but it also allows us to seamlessly complete development. }
10... O-O-O 11. Nxe6 fxe6 12. Rxe6 Bd6 13. Bg5
{ Amazingly, this is the most popular move on club level - an outright blunder! }
13... Bxh2+ 14. Nxh2 Qxg5 15. Nf3 Qf5
{ And Black stands much better with the extra material and the more active pieces. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) King's Gambit"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. --
{ If I had to guess about an opening that you will likely get a fair bit on the black side of e4-e5, it would be the King’s Gambit.    There is an everlasting appeal to the opening that scored so many marvelous victories for White in the 1800s, including one of the most famous game ever: The Immortal Game between Anderssen and Kieseretzky.   Nowadays the engines are blasting sizeable holes on most early gambits and the King’s Gambit is no exception. Although the opening is not refuted per se, it certainly offers no advantage for White! }
*

