1. e4 e5 2. f4
{ The King's Gambit is an enduring legacy of the romantic era.   This opening is particularly popular on club level as it is an aggressive attacking opening with plenty of tactical potential.   However, when countered correctly, Black faces absolutely no problems at all. }
2... d5
{ This move technically introduces the Falkbeer Countergambit, however, in our case it is going to be simply a move-order trick to return to the main lines, avoiding some sidelines along the way. }
3. fxe5 { Loses instantly to: } 3... Qh4+ 4. g3 Qxe4+ *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) King's Gambit"]
[Black "3.exd5 exf4 4.Bc4 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. f4
{ The King's Gambit is an enduring legacy of the romantic era.   This opening is particularly popular on club level as it is an aggressive attacking opening with plenty of tactical potential.   However, when countered correctly, Black faces absolutely no problems at all. }
2... d5
{ This move technically introduces the Falkbeer Countergambit, however, in our case it is going to be simply a move-order trick to return to the main lines, avoiding some sidelines along the way. }
3. exd5 { 3.Nf3  exf4  transposes into the main line after a few more moves. }
3... exf4
{ And thus, we are back in the main lines of the King's Gambit,  3...e4  would be the Falkbeer countergambit. }
4. Bc4
{ This move allows us to transition into a better version of the King's Bishop Gambit. I.e. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.f4  exf4  3.Bc4  Qh4+  4.Kf1  d5  and here White has the necessary  5.Bxd5   In our version, White has already captured on d5 with the pawn, and thus had to settle for the inferior capture. }
4... Qh4+
{ If this check is allowed, generally speaking, we should go for it.   White's idea is to gain a tempo on the Queen with Nf3, but in my view, this will not compensate for the lost castling rights. }
5. Kf1 Bd6
{ Black secures f4 and also blockades the d5 pawn, reducing the power of the c4 Bishop. }
6. Nf3 Qh6
{ The Queen stands well here for multiple reasons: It defends f4, keeps an eye on the h2 pawn, and also allows the g8 Knight to develop to both f6 and e7. }
7. Nc3 Ne7
{ This is a prudent move by Black. From e7 we can go to both g6 and f5. The latter will prove particularly effective when White plays d2-d4. }
8. d4 O-O { Black calmly completes development. } 9. Kf2 Nd7
{ And Black stands clearly better.   The White King is insecure and the f4 pawn facilitates aggressive kingside plans: We aim to complete development with Nf6 and then invade with Nf5-Ng4-Ne3. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) King's Gambit"]
[Black "3.exd5 exf4 4.Bb5+"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. f4
{ The King's Gambit is an enduring legacy of the romantic era.   This opening is particularly popular on club level as it is an aggressive attacking opening with plenty of tactical potential.   However, when countered correctly, Black faces absolutely no problems at all. }
2... d5
{ This move technically introduces the Falkbeer Countergambit, however, in our case it is going to be simply a move-order trick to return to the main lines, avoiding some sidelines along the way. }
3. exd5 { 3.Nf3  exf4  transposes into the main line after a few more moves. }
3... exf4
{ And thus, we are back in the main lines of the King's Gambit,  3...e4  would be the Falkbeer countergambit. }
4. Bb5+ c6 5. dxc6 Nxc6
{ This variation leads to a peculiar pawn structure where both players have a 4 vs 2 pawn majority.   Although our pawns are doubled, the f4 pawn is actually a great asset as it restricts the development of the c1 Bishop and allows us various kingside plans such as the expansion with g7-g5-g4, or the invasion of the e3 square with Ng8-f6-g4-e3. }
6. Nf3 Bd6
{ This move allows Black to remain flexible with the development of the g8 Knight. }
7. d4 Ne7
{ Although this is not the engine's preferred choice, I opted for this move as it makes more sense in this structure: the Knight from e7 can go to g6 to defend the f4 pawn or head to f5 and aim for the tender e3 square. }
8. O-O { 8.d5??  Nxd5!  9.Qxd5  Bb4+  10.Nc3  Qxd5-+ } 8... O-O 9. c3 Nf5
{ Black has a pleasant position. Our plan is simply to invade via e3 with Re8 and then Ne3. }
*

