3... exf4
{ And thus, we are back in the main lines of the King's Gambit,  3...e4  would be the Falkbeer countergambit. }
4. Nf3
{ Without a doubt the best move for White as virtually everything else allows Qh4+. }
4... Nf6 5. c4 c6
{ This move is very important! We eliminate the d5 pawn in order to accelerate the development of the b8 Knight. }
6. dxc6
{ This is the most popular move on club level, but it allows us a very comfortable edge: }
6... Nxc6 7. d4 Bg4
{ It turns out that our lead in development is significant enough to cause major trouble in the center! The d4 pawn is too vulnerable. }
8. Be2 { Relatively best. } 8... Bxf3 9. Bxf3 Qe7+
{ And White is stuck for a good way to deal with the check. } 10. Kf1 O-O-O 11.
d5 Qc7
{ Black will follow up with Bc5, ensuring that the White King is permanently exposed in the middle. }
*

