1. e4 e5 2. f4
{ The King's Gambit is an enduring legacy of the romantic era.   This opening is particularly popular on club level as it is an aggressive attacking opening with plenty of tactical potential.   However, when countered correctly, Black faces absolutely no problems at all. }
2... d5
{ This move technically introduces the Falkbeer Countergambit, however, in our case it is going to be simply a move-order trick to return to the main lines, avoiding some sidelines along the way. }
3. exd5 { 3.Nf3  exf4  transposes into the main line after a few more moves. }
3... exf4
{ And thus, we are back in the main lines of the King's Gambit,  3...e4  would be the Falkbeer countergambit. }
4. Nf3
{ Without a doubt the best move for White as virtually everything else allows Qh4+. }
4... Nf6 5. c4 c6
{ This move is very important! We eliminate the d5 pawn in order to accelerate the development of the b8 Knight. }
6. dxc6
{ This is the most popular move on club level, but it allows us a very comfortable edge: }
