1. e4 e5 2. f4
{ The King's Gambit is an enduring legacy of the romantic era.   This opening is particularly popular on club level as it is an aggressive attacking opening with plenty of tactical potential.   However, when countered correctly, Black faces absolutely no problems at all. }
2... d5
{ This move technically introduces the Falkbeer Countergambit, however, in our case it is going to be simply a move-order trick to return to the main lines, avoiding some sidelines along the way. }
3. exd5 { 3.Nf3  exf4  transposes into the main line after a few more moves. }
3... exf4
{ And thus, we are back in the main lines of the King's Gambit,  3...e4  would be the Falkbeer countergambit. }
4. Nf3
{ Without a doubt the best move for White as virtually everything else allows Qh4+. }
4... Nf6 5. Bc4
{ This is the best move in this position. On club level, however,  5.c4  is much more popular. }
5... Nxd5 6. O-O Be6
{ This is a very handy move here as it supports the d5 Knight and also shields the King from annoying checks along the e-file. }
7. Bb3
{ This prophylactic move secures the Bishop and allows White to play for both d2-d4 and c2-c4. }
7... c5
{ With this move we aim to contest White's central ambitions and deny the d4-c4 pawn formation. }
8. d4 cxd4
{ This move leads to an equalish endgame with a tiny edge for Black. } 9. Nxd4
Bc5 { This pin gains crucial time for us to disallow the threatened Nxe6. } 10.
Kh1 Bxd4
{ Although giving up the Bishop for the Knight is undesired, this trade allows us to further pull ahead in development. }
11. Qxd4 O-O 12. c4 Nc6
{ The reward for the previous trade on d4: This delicious tempo means that White has to delay the development of the queenside. }
13. Qe4 Ndb4 14. Bxf4 Qd3
{ And Black stands slightly better due to the better piece mobilty and lead in development.  We look to complete development with Rad8 and Rfe8. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.1) King's Gambit - Model Games"]
[Black "Plenca, J. vs. Kuljasevic, D., Mali Losinj 2018"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. f4 d5 3. exd5 exf4 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bc4 Nxd5 6. O-O Be6 7. Bb3 c5 8.
d4 cxd4 9. Nxd4 Bc5 10. Kh1 Bxd4 11. Qxd4 O-O 12. Bxd5
{ Our theory goes with c4, but the text is also a valid idea in order to regain f4. }
12... Nc6 13. Qxf4 Qxd5 14. Nc3 Qc4
{ 14...Qh5  seems like a very good alternative too, in which case Black would have a wider range of plans including targeting the c2- and g2-squares. }
15. Be3 Qxf4 16. Rxf4
{ This endgame should not be winnable but it definitely requires White to be careful.   Our main trump cards are the control of the d-file and the targetable queenside pawns. }
16... Rfd8 17. Nb5 Rac8 18. c3 Rd3
{ Nice technique, combining positional and tactical elements. } 19. Bg1
{ 19.Bxa7  Nxa7  20.Nxa7  Ra8  21.Nb5  Rxa2!  was the clever point behind Rd3. }
19... a6 20. Nd4 Bd5
{ The Bishop stands remarkably well here as the g2 pawn is a tender target. }
21. Nb3 Bxb3
{ Black gives up the powerful Bishop in order to obtain a different type of advantage: The domination of the 2nd rank. }
22. axb3 Rd2 23. Rb1 Re8 24. Rf2 Red8 25. Re1 f6 26. Rfe2 Rxe2 27. Rxe2 Rd1
{ Gradually, Black's advantage becomes more and more tangible.   Note the vast difference in piece activity! Kuljasevic mops up the rest in style: }
28. h3 Kf7 29. Kh2 h5 30. Bc5 h4 31. b4 g5 32. g3 hxg3+ 33. Kxg3 Rd3+ 34. Kg2
Ne5 35. Be3 Kg6 36. Bd4 Nc6 37. Bf2 Kf5 38. Bg3 Kg6 39. Be1 Kf7 40. Bd2 Ne7 41.
Rf2 Kg6 42. c4 Nf5 43. Bc3 Ne3+ 44. Kh2 f5 45. c5 f4 46. Be5 Kf5 47. Bd6 Ke4
48. Kh1 Nf5 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
