[White "1.1) King's Gambit - Model Games"]
[Black "Polgar, Sofia vs. Waitzkin, Joshua, Bermuda 1995"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. f4 d5 3. exd5 exf4 4. Bc4 Qh4+ 5. Kf1 Bd6 6. Nf3 Qh5 7. Nc3 Ne7 8.
d4 O-O 9. Kf2 Nd7
{ This is where our theory stops, so this game is going to be a real treat to see how a better position turns into a decisive attack. }
10. Bb3 Nf6
{ One of the greatest features of this line is the fact that it is super intuitive. The Black pieces are going to overrun the kingside. }
11. Re1 Bg4 12. h3 Nf5
{ The attack on the white King is already irresistible. } 13. Nb5
{ 13.hxg4  Loses beautifully to:  13...Nxg4+  14.Kf1   14.Ke2  Rae8+  15.Kd2  Nf2  With a spectacular queen trap!  14...Ng3+  15.Kg1  Qh1 }
13... Rae8
{ The development and overall activity of the Black pieces is nothing short of awe inspiring. }
14. Nxd6 Bxf3 15. Nxe8 { 15.Qxf3  Qh4+  Is also terminal. } 15... Bxd1 16.
Nxf6+ gxf6 17. Bxf4 Bf3
{ The last nail in the coffin. I give the rest of the game without commentary as it is a matter of mopping up @@StartBracket@@and actually Black kind of messed it up@@EndBracket@@. }
18. Bxc7 { 18.gxf3  Qh4+  Regains the Bishop on f4. } 18... Nxd4 19. c4 Kh8 20.
Bd1 Bxd1 21. Raxd1 Nc2 22. Re2 Nb4 23. Bd6 Rg8 24. g4 Qh4+ 25. Kg2 Na6 26. Rf1
Nb8 27. Bg3 Qh6 28. Re7 Qd2+ 29. Rf2 Qd4 30. Bh4 Rg6 31. Rxf7 Qxc4 32. Rf8+ Kg7
33. Rxb8 Qxd5+ 34. Kh2 h5 35. Rc2 Kh7 36. Rc7+ Rg7 37. Rbxb7 Qd2+ 38. Kg1 Qd1+
39. Kg2 Qd2+ 40. Bf2 Qd5+ 41. Kh2 Qxb7 42. Rxb7 Rxb7 43. Bd4 hxg4 44. hxg4 Kg6
45. Kg3 Rd7 46. Be3 Kf7 47. Kf4 Ke6 48. a3 Rc7 49. Bd2 Rc4+ 50. Kf3 Rc5 51. Bc3
a5 52. Kf4 Rc4+ 53. Kg3 a4 54. Kf3 Rc8 55. Kg3 Rd8 56. Kf3 Rd1 57. Kg3 Kf7 58.
Kf3 Kg6 59. Kf4 Rd7 60. Kf3 Kg5 61. Ke2 Rd6 62. Kf3 Rd3+ 63. Kg2 Rxc3 64. bxc3
Kxg4 65. c4 Kf4 *

