[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Danish Gambit"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. --
{ Similar to the King’s Gambit, the Danish is also a bold and enterprising choice, mostly played by aggressive attackers.   It’s heyday is already well behind us, and many variations are known to theory to at least equalize for Black.   Once again, I chose variations that allow no attack at all to White, thus, securing an edge both psychologically and on the board. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Danish Gambit"]
[Black "2.d4 exd4 3.c3 d5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

{  } 1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4 3. c3
{ The Danish Gambit is one of the most notable examples of the Romantic chess style, stemming from the mid-1800s.   The idea, as is very common with most gambits, is to sacrifice a pawn or two in order to accelerate White's development and obtain superior central control.   This opening, just like many other early gambits is rarely seen on a professional level as they allow Black to equalize very easily @@StartBracket@@often even get the upper hand!@@EndBracket@@. }
3... d5
{ This central counter-punch is going to be our key idea to combat the gambit.  Please note that the alternative  3...Qe7  @@StartBracket@@which we will examinehere@@EndBracket@@- an extremely ugly, yet super effective move- is considered to be best here by most 1.e4 e5 experts, including the legendary Jan Gustafsson! }
4. Qxd4 { 4.Qxd4 looks terrible but is actually quite tricky to refute! } 4...
Be6
{ For the time being, we don't want to invite the pins on either knight, although in the long run, it will be inevitable. }
5. Nf3 Nf6 6. Bg5 Nc6 7. Bb5
{ Although the pins allow White to dodge some of the threats, they certainly don't pose problems to us. In fact,  White will likely have to trade bishops for knights soon. }
7... dxe4 8. Bxf6 Qxf6 9. Bxc6+
{ 9.Qxe4  O-O-O  10.Bxc6  bxc6  leads to the same position. } 9... bxc6 10.
Qxe4 O-O-O
{ As so often, we happily castle into a 'loose' structure as the king is perfectly safe, but our initiative is increasing further! }
11. O-O { 11.Qxc6??  Rd1+-+  wins either the rook or the queen. } 11... Bd5 12.
Qg4+ Qe6 13. Qxe6+ { Only move. } 13... Bxe6
{ Black is slightly better in this endgame due to our better development and the bishop pair.   It's a suitable moment to bust the myth that we are worse here because of our damaged pawn structure on the queenside - the truth is that White has no chance whatsoever to target these pawns or even to exploit some of the weak squares around them. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Danish Gambit"]
[Black "2.d4 exd4 3.c3 d5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

{  } 1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4 3. c3
{ The Danish Gambit is one of the most notable examples of the Romantic chess style, stemming from the mid-1800s.   The idea, as is very common with most gambits, is to sacrifice a pawn or two in order to accelerate White's development and obtain superior central control.   This opening, just like many other early gambits is rarely seen on a professional level as they allow Black to equalize very easily @@StartBracket@@often even get the upper hand!@@EndBracket@@. }
3... d5
{ This central counter-punch is going to be our key idea to combat the gambit.  Please note that the alternative  3...Qe7  @@StartBracket@@which we will examinehere@@EndBracket@@- an extremely ugly, yet super effective move- is considered to be best here by most 1.e4 e5 experts, including the legendary Jan Gustafsson! }
4. exd5 Nf6
{ This is a major detour from the well-known  4...Qxd5  , which leads to a very dry and equal endgame.  The text aims to recapture on d5 with the Knight, a far more optimal scenario, as we have learned from Grandpa Nimzowitch that the Knight is the ultimate blockader! }
5. c4 { This greedy move gets punished quickly: } 5... Bb4+ 6. Bd2 Bxd2+ 7.
Nxd2 O-O 8. Bd3 c6
{ And Black takes over the initiative.   Re8 is coming and the White minor pieces are very passively placed. }
*

