{ The Danish Gambit is one of the most notable examples of the Romantic chess style, stemming from the mid-1800s.   The idea, as is very common with most gambits, is to sacrifice a pawn or two in order to accelerate White's development and obtain superior central control.   This opening, just like many other early gambits is rarely seen on a professional level as they allow Black to equalize very easily @@StartBracket@@often even get the upper hand!@@EndBracket@@. }
3... d5
{ This central counter-punch is going to be our key idea to combat the gambit.  Please note that the alternative  3...Qe7  @@StartBracket@@which we will examinehere@@EndBracket@@- an extremely ugly, yet super effective move- is considered to be best here by most 1.e4 e5 experts, including the legendary Jan Gustafsson! }
4. exd5 Nf6
{ This is a major detour from the well-known  4...Qxd5  , which leads to a very dry and equal endgame.  The text aims to recapture on d5 with the Knight, a far more optimal scenario, as we have learned from Grandpa Nimzowitch that the Knight is the ultimate blockader! }
5. cxd4 Nxd5 6. Nc3 Bb4 7. Bd2 O-O
{ Black's development plays itself and now White needs to be careful as the open e-file offers Black an easy path to the White King. }
8. Nf3 c5
{ With this move Black challenges White to an immediate fight, which makes perfect sense, given that the White King is still two moves away from castling. }
9. dxc5
{ This terrible move is actually the most frequently played one in the Lichess database! }
9... Nxc3 10. Bxc3 Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 Re8+ 12. Be2 Qe7
{ And White has major issues completing development, while the queenside pawn structure is also in shambles. }
*

