{  } 1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4 3. c3
{ The Danish Gambit is one of the most notable examples of the Romantic chess style, stemming from the mid-1800s.   The idea, as is very common with most gambits, is to sacrifice a pawn or two in order to accelerate White's development and obtain superior central control.   This opening, just like many other early gambits is rarely seen on a professional level as they allow Black to equalize very easily @@StartBracket@@often even get the upper hand!@@EndBracket@@. }
3... Qe7
{ Despite the very obvious downsides of this move @@StartBracket@@blocking the f8 Bishop and moving the Queen too soon@@EndBracket@@, it transpires that White simply does not have any adequate ways to defend the e4 pawn! }
4. cxd4 Qxe4+ 5. Be3 Nf6 6. Nc3 Bb4
{ It already is apparent that White will not have enough counterplay for the loss of a vitally important central pawn. }
7. Nf3 Ng4
{ Another slightly counterintuitive, yet very important move! Black aims to trade on e3 and clog up the e-file. }
8. Bd3 Nxe3 9. Bxe4 Nxd1 10. Rxd1 d6
{ And Black stand much better with the extra pawn and the 2 Bishops.   The follow-up plan is Nd7-f6 and O-O. }
