[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. d4 { The Center Game kicks off as if it were a Danish Gambit... }
2... exd4 3. Qxd4
{ ...but then it takes a sharp turn towards a different direction! As mentioned, this looks mostly like a reversed Scandinavian. }
3... Nc6 4. Qe3
{ This is White's best move. The queen can't be easily attacked on e3 and she also has easy access to the g3-square, which often turns out to be a good spot to pressure the black kingside. }
4... Nf6 5. e5
{ 5.e5 is an important side variation here as it is quite popular on the club level. This move leads to trouble for White by force, but Black needs to play aggressive, non-compromising chess! }
5... Ng4 6. Qe2 d6
{ This sacrifice is almost 'natural' in such positions. We should turn on 'the aggro' here and go after White in the most brutal fashion! }
7. exd6+ Be6 { Black's lead in development is already off the charts. } 8. dxc7
Qxc7 9. Nc3 O-O-O
{ White is completely lost here. The following variation beautifully demonstrates how a lead in development should be turned into a quick win: }
10. Nf3 Bb4 11. Bd2 Bxc3 12. Bxc3 Rhe8
{ White has no defence against the looming discovered attack on the e-file. } *

