1. e4 e5 2. d4 { The Center Game kicks off as if it were a Danish Gambit... }
2... exd4 3. Qxd4
{ ...but then it takes a sharp turn towards a different direction! As mentioned, this looks mostly like a reversed Scandinavian. }
3... Nc6 4. Qe3
{ This is White's best move. The queen can't be easily attacked on e3 and she also has easy access to the g3-square, which often turns out to be a good spot to pressure the black kingside. }
4... Nf6 5. e5
{ 5.e5 is an important side variation here as it is quite popular on the club level. This move leads to trouble for White by force, but Black needs to play aggressive, non-compromising chess! }
5... Ng4 6. Qe4 Ngxe5
{ This piece sac is definitely the best way to punish White's extremely provocative play. }
7. f4 d5
{ The chase continues... White will have to play an embarrassing number of moves with the queen before starting development. }
8. Qe3 d4 9. Qe4 Bb4+
{ This check is a key component to our attack as it allows us to castle whenever needed! }
10. Bd2 Qh4+ 11. g3 Qg4
{ Try to remember this motif: the idea is to keep the f-pawn pinned and also to play ...Qg6, removing the pin on the e-file. }
12. Be2 Qg6
{ Black is already much better. After the queen trade, we remain a pawn to the good with better development! }
