3. d4
{ This is the not-so-scary 'Urusov Gambit'. As usual, we just take what's on offer! }
3... exd4 4. Nf3 Bb4+
{ This is the engine's preference and it is indeed the most straightforward way to combat White's ambitions. }
5. c3 dxc3 6. bxc3 d5
{ This superb intermezzo ruins White's party, who was hoping for  6...Bc5  and then  7.e5! }
7. exd5 Be7
{ By returning the gambit pawn, Black has obtained optimal piece placement. On the other hand, White's pawn structure is split and the c4 Bishop is a very sad piece.  Note that  7...Bd6  is also possible but I preferred to eliminate the option of a pin by Bg5. }
8. O-O O-O 9. Re1 c6 10. dxc6 Qxd1 11. Rxd1 Nxc6
{ And Black is clearly better in this queenless middlegame, due to the split white pawns on the queenside. Our follow-up is Bg4 and then Rac8. }
