[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Bishop's Opening"]
[Black "2.Bc4 Nf6 3.d3 c6 4.Nf3 d5 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4 { This move aptly introduces the 'Bishop's Opening'. } 2... Nf6
{ This is best and is also in sync with our other lines. After  3.Nc3  Nxe4  we transpose to our Vienna lines, which we will examinehere. }
3. d3
{ This is by far the most played move here. White often transposes into other openings such as the Vienna and the Italian, and sometimes even King's Gambit lines with f4.   Our main move denies all transitions and dictates the character of the game. }
3... c6
{ Utilising the fact that White exerts no pressure on the e5 pawn, Black ambitiously aims to execute the d7-d5 break very early on. }
4. Nf3 d5 5. Bb3
{ White should delay the capture on d5 as it denies Black playing Nc6. } 5...
Bd6 6. Nc3
{ The best and most popular move. White is trying to provoke a d5-d4 push, which would allow the b3 Bishop to fully come to life.   Also, the Ne2-Ng3 maneuver is something White is keen to do anyway! }
6... h6
{ It is not very often that I attach an exclam to the 'bunny ears', so enjoy the moment while you can!  The idea is that d5 is actually rather risky to capture and so Black uses this time to deny White the annoying Bg5 pin.  Note that on Super GM level  6...dxe4  has been preferred, but to be perfectly honest, the capture makes more sense to me once Ng5 has been denied. }
7. exd5 cxd5 8. O-O Be6
{ Although this move is going to cost us the Bishop pair, the center formation will remain undisturbed, allowing us a comfortable game. }
9. Nb5 Nc6 10. Nxd6+ Qxd6 11. Re1
{ This move is actually a sneaky threat that we need to respect!   White is planning Nxe5 followed by Bf4 and d3-d4, demolishing the center and winning material! }
11... Bg4
{ It definitely should feel insecure to further expose our King on the e-file, but the concrete variations prove this move to be best! }
12. h3 Bh5 { As it turns out, we actually want to induce g2-g4! } 13. g4 Nxg4
{ This well-known piece sacrifice is very effective here, as it is combined with our dominant and mobile pawn center. }
14. Nxe5
{ White tries to counterattack, but has a response against this one too! }
14... Ngxe5 15. Qxh5 g6 16. Qg4 Qe7
{ A highly unusual way to create a double attack: We are threatening with Nxg4 as well as Nf3, and White can't stop both! }
*

