[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4 Nf6 3. d3 c6 4. Bb3 d5 5. Nf3 Bd6 6. exd5 cxd5 7. Bg5 Be6 8.
O-O
{ This is inaccurate,  8.Nc3  is our line. Black now has more options to hold the center. }
8... Nc6 9. Nc3 Bc7 10. Re1 a6
{ This is to deny Nb5, but also to take the sting out of the Ba4 ideas, as now they can be met by b5. }
11. Bh4 O-O 12. h3 Re8 13. Nh2 Qd6
{ This is an idea we have seen in our lines.   Black allows the damaged kingside pawn structure as it reinforces the center and opens the g-file for a kingside attack. }
14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Qh5 Nd4
{ This very healthy-looking centralization is actually inaccurate! It was imperative to stop Ng4 at all costs!   15...f5  is a fantastic move with a mind-blowing idea behind it!  16.Qg5+  Kf8  17.Qh6+  Ke7!  it turns out that our central dominance is so strong that the King can safely walk to the middle @@StartBracket@@and then to the queenside@@EndBracket@@, without getting harmed.  Note that our threats with e5-e4 and Rg8 are still very dangerous! }
16. Ng4 { Black now needs to defend accurately. } 16... Bd8 17. Re3 Kh8 18. Nh6
Rf8 19. Rg3
{ White returns the favor. Although the Rook may threatening, in reality, White has no further threats to boot. Ne2 was much better, with the idea of bringing more pieces to the kingside. }
19... f5 { All of a sudden the Black pawns become an unstoppable force! } 20.
Re1 f4 21. Rg4 f5 { The game is over as the white Rook has nowhere to go. } 22.
Rg5 Bxg5 23. Qxg5 Nf3+ { Timoscenko finishes in style. The rest is simple. }
24. gxf3 Rg8 25. Nxg8 Rxg8 26. Qxg8+ Kxg8 27. d4 e4 28. Kf1 Kf8 29. Ke2 Bf7 30.
Rg1 Bh5 31. Bxd5 Bxf3+ 32. Ke1 Qf6 33. Rg8+ Ke7 34. Bb3 e3 35. fxe3 Qh4+ 36.
Kd2 Qf2+ 37. Kd3 Be2+ 38. Nxe2 Qxe3+ 39. Kc4 Qxe2+ 40. Kb4 f3 41. Rg7+ Kf6 42.
Rxb7 f2 43. Bc4 f1=Q 44. Rb6+ Kg5 45. Bxe2 Qxe2 46. c4 f4 47. h4+ Kf5 48. Kc5
f3 49. Rb7 f2 50. Rf7+ Ke6 *

