[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nc3
{ This move introduces the Vienna game. The most common idea behind the setup is to play a 'delayed king's gambit'. }
2... Nf6
{ 2...Nc6  is also known here but the text is the most challenging. Black is preparing the d7-d5 counterpunch. }
3. Bc4 Nxe4
{ This pseudo-sacrifice is a very common motif in many e4-e5 openings, and certainly one to remember! }
4. Qh5 { This move is by far White's best, threatening both e5 and f7. } 4...
Nd6 5. Qxe5+ { This variation allows Black an easy way to equality: } 5... Qe7
6. Qxe7+ Bxe7 7. Bb3 Nf5 8. Nd5 { 8.Nf3  c6!  And Black has easy equality. }
8... Bd8
{ And in this Fischer Random-like position Black has no issues after c6 followed by d5. }
