[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Vienna "]
[Black "2.Nc3 Nf6 3.g3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nc3
{ This move introduces the Vienna game. The most common idea behind the setup is to play a 'delayed king's gambit'. }
2... Nf6
{ 2...Nc6  is also known here but the text is the most challenging. Black is preparing the d7-d5 counterpunch. }
3. g3
{ This move hopes to steer the game towards positional pastures, however, once again, we have different ideas in mind! }
3... d5 4. exd5 c6
{ This is our key move. The idea is play a reverse Danish Gambit, where White's g3 move is more of a hindrance than a help. <---- Note the alliteration! }
5. Bg2
{ Is way too timid and allows us to grab the initiative without even losing material. }
5... cxd5 6. d4 exd4 7. Qxd4 Nc6 8. Qd1 d4
{ If an IQP is not blockaded, it means we have a green light for thrusting forward! }
9. Nce2 Bc5 10. Nf3 O-O
{ Black has a comfortable edge due to the space advantage provided by the d4 pawn. We should follow with Bf5, Re8, Qd7 etc with easy play. }
*

