{ This move introduces the Vienna game. The most common idea behind the setup is to play a 'delayed king's gambit'. }
2... Nf6
{ 2...Nc6  is also known here but the text is the most challenging. Black is preparing the d7-d5 counterpunch. }
3. f4 d5
{ With this move we echo our setup vs the King's Gambit. The idea is identical: immediately counterpunching in the center. }
4. fxe5 Nxe4 5. Qf3 f5
{ In my opinion the best and most solid move.   Also of the same opinion is the founder of the legendary Chicken Chess Club and author of the 1.e4-e5 LTR - Jan Gustafsson.   When it comes to e4-e5 matters, we should certainly trust his expert opinion! }
6. exf6
{ Is just plain bad as now the White Queen really does look out of place on f3. }
6... Nxf6 7. d4 Bb4
{ 7...Nc6  is also playable, but the text leads to a cool and often overlooked concept I thought would be good to include in the course: }
8. Qe3+ Kf7
{ This is it! Black voluntarily surrenders castling right in order to expose the white King! }
9. Be2 Re8 10. Qd3 Kg8
{ Castling 'by hand' does the job, and our King is perfectly safe! } 11. Bg5
{ After  11.Nf3  b6!  White is busted due to the deadly Ba6 threat. } 11... Qd6
{ It is important to get out of this pin immediately to threaten with Ne4, thus forcing the trade on f6. }
12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. O-O-O c6
{ And Black stands clearly better with the 2 Bishops. Our plan is to complete development with Bf5 and Nd7.   Note that White's Nf3 is met by Bxc3 when the Queen can't retake due to the hanging e2 Bishop! }
