[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nc3
{ This move introduces the Vienna game. The most common idea behind the setup is to play a 'delayed king's gambit'. }
2... Nf6
{ Nc6 is also known here but the text is the most challenging. Black is preparing the d7-d5 counterpunch. }
3. f4 d5
{ With this move we echo our setup vs the King's Gambit. The idea is identical: immediately counterpunching in the center. }
4. fxe5 Nxe4 5. Qf3 f5
{ In my opinion the best and most solid move.   Also of the same opinion is the founder of the legendary Chicken Chess Club and author of the 1.e4-e5 LTR - Jan Gustafsson.   When it comes to e4-e5 matters, we should certainly trust his expert opinion! }
6. d3 Nxc3 7. bxc3 d4
{ This is a key idea in this structure: Black prevents White from completing the pawn chain with d3-d4. }
8. Qg3
{ This move defends e5, prepares the Be2-h5 tricks and also at times allows Nf3. }
8... Nc6 9. Be2 Be6
{ Black has very simple and natural developing moves to play.   The text also dodges the Bh5 threat as White no longer has the dangerous sac on g6, due to the eventual Bf7 block. }
10. Bf3 { 10.Bh5+  g6  11.Bxg6+??  hxg6  12.Qxg6+  Bf7  13.Qxf5  Rh5-+ } 10...
Qd7
{ Once again, easy does it! Black is now ready to castle Queenside, an idea that we often execute in this setup! }
11. Ne2 dxc3 12. O-O Bc5+ 13. Kh1 O-O-O
{ And Black has a better position and an extra pawn!   Our play is simply to play h6 followed by g5 and f4 with complete domination on the kingside! }
