1. e4 e5 2. Nc3
{ This move introduces the Vienna game. The most common idea behind the setup is to play a 'delayed king's gambit'. }
2... Nf6
{ 2...Nc6  is also known here but the text is the most challenging. Black is preparing the d7-d5 counterpunch. }
3. f4 d5
{ With this move we echo our setup vs the King's Gambit. The idea is identical: immediately counterpunching in the center. }
4. fxe5 Nxe4 5. Nf3 Bc5
{ This move seems counter-intuitive as it induces d2-d4. The benefit of doing so is that this way we get to retain the Knight on e4!   The other main line goes with Be7 when White kicks the e4 Knight with d3. }
6. d4 Bb4 7. Bd2 c5
{ It is important to play this move before Nc6, so we can pressure the center with all our might! }
8. Nxe4 dxe4
{ Another important tempo which disallows White to focus on completing development. }
9. Bxb4 cxb4 10. Ng1
{ A very sad move, after which we will easily grab the initiative. } 10... O-O
{ Whilst Black's development seems super logical and easy @@StartBracket@@Nc6 and Be6 or g4@@EndBracket@@, White in contrast finds it difficult to develop harmoniously. }
11. Bc4 Nc6 12. c3 bxc3 13. bxc3
{ This is precisely how the game Andreikin - Kramnik went, but a beginner repertoire must uphold the highest standards and so now we deviate from the play of the Russian ex-World Champ! }
13... Qc7
{ The queen is super effective here, aiming down the c-file. Black stands much better as our threats are becoming way too much to handle.  For a deeper explanation please play through the following clickable:   14.Bb3  Nxe5!!  carnage time! This move demolishes White's defense.  15.dxe5  Qxc3+  16.Kf1  Qxe5  17.Ne2  Bg4-+  with a deadly attack.  White will never be able to connect the rooks and put up a fight. }
