{ The black central pawns are too much of a nuisance here. } 16. Qe2 Qd5 17.
Nc2 Rb8 18. Rac1 Be6 19. Nb4 Rxb4
{ Black eliminates the only piece that holds the defense together. Inspired chess! }
20. cxb4 Qxd4+ 21. Qf2 e3 22. Qe2 Bd5
{ Black can freely pick off the white Pawns while White has nothing meaningful to play for. The rest is just agony. }
23. e6 Qxb4 24. Qg4 h5 25. Qe2 Qe4 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5.1) Vienna - Model Games "]
[Black "Kuzin, Anton vs. Afromeev, Vladimir, Tula 2006"]
[Result "*"]

{ This game is a textbook case of how easily things can get spiral out of control for White in the 'Dracula' variation. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bc4 Nxe4 4. Qh5 Nd6 5. Bb3 Nc6 6. Nb5 g6 7. Qf3 f5 8.
Qd5 Qe7 9. Nxc7+ Kd8 10. Nxa8 b6 11. Nf3
{ This move is inaccurate here, d3 is the most challenging continuation. }
11... Bb7
{ Nothing describes the dangers lurking around better than the fact that Stockfish already heavily favor Black here! }
12. d4 Nxd4 13. Bg5
{ White hopes get out of trouble by offering trades, but this is to no avail. }
13... Nxf3+ 14. Qxf3 Qxg5 15. Bd5 Bxd5
{ Black errs in return. Much better would have been:   15...Ba6!  When White can castle to neither side.  16.h4  Qh5!  Typical computer chess. The engine evaluates this move as the absolute best, as the resulting endgame is hopeless for White. E. g.  17.Qxh5  gxh5  18.Rh3  Ne4?  19.Rd1  Nf6  20.Rb3  Bc5  21.a4  d6  22.a5  Nxd5  23.Rxd5  Kd7  And Black is clearly winning! }
16. Qxd5 Qf4 17. O-O Qe4
{ Black follows the same policy as in the above sideline: trade down, win the Knight on a8, walk away with a victory. }
18. Rad1 Kc8 19. Rfe1 Qxd5 20. Rxd5 Kb7 21. Nxb6 axb6
{ This endgame is winning for Black, but Afromeev's technique is a delight to watch! }
22. Rdxe5 Kc6 23. b3 Bg7 24. Re7 Bf6 25. R7e3 b5
{ Black wants to blockade the entire queenside pawn mass. } 26. Rd1 b4 27. Red3
Be5 28. g3 Ne4
{ Another great call: Black gives up a pawn to maximize the activity of his minor pieces. }
29. Rxd7 Bd6 30. Rf7 Bc5 31. Rf1 Rd8 32. Rxh7 Nxf2 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Ponziani"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. --
{ The Ponziani is a surprisingly old opening, the first traces of this opening can be found in the late 15th century. It was later championed by the legendary British player Howard Staunton.   The lovely historical touch and the centuries-long longevity, however, are truly running out as nowadays many known lines offer Black at least comfortable equality.    Notable YouTubers have brought it back to the fore and so it is now gaining traction on club level again.   As I consider this opening a slight provocation, we shall respond to it with aggression and energetic play! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Ponziani"]
[Black "2.Nf3 Nc6 3.c3 d5 4.exd5 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3
{ This funky-looking move introduces the Ponziani.   White's idea is to conquer the center with d2-d4, which, of course, we are not going idly allow... }
3... d5
{ This is the most thematic central countermeasure. Black strikes in the middle before White can get d4 in.   Note that c3 will turn out to be a rather ugly move in many variations as it will greatly hinder the development of the White's queenside. }
4. exd5
{ Shockingly, this move is the most popular one on club level, immediately handing over the initiative to Black. }
4... Qxd5 5. d4 Bf5
{ It is imperative here not to commit the cardinal sin of capturing on d4, which would release the b1 Knight.   Black now has the opportunity to castle queenside, further pressuring the central d4 pawn. }
6. dxe5
{ This move nets an extra pawn and a miserable queenless middlegame for White. }
6... Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 O-O-O+ 8. Nbd2 Nge7
{ The Knight is en route to g6, aiming to recover the pawn on e5. } 9. Bb5
{ This is White's best attempt to hang on to the extra pawn. } 9... g5
{ This sensational thrust sets the board on fire and disallows White from consolidating.   The pawn thrust introduces a host of complications: g5-g4 is pending, the f8 Bishop can now go to g7, and also, if White takes on g5, Black will activate the Rook along the g-file. }
10. Nxg5 Nxe5
{ This capture is also a great defensive measure as now f7 is safely guarded. }
11. f4 Rg8 12. Re1 h6
{ The mutual 'stand off' always favors the better-developed side, which is definitely Black. }
13. Rxe5 hxg5 14. fxg5 Rxg5
{ And White is now in serious trouble.   Apart from the discovered attack on the e5 rook @@StartBracket@@Bc2+ and Bg4+@@EndBracket@@, Black is also threatening to simply capture on g2.   White's position is on the verge of collapse. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Ponziani"]
[Black "2.Nf3 Nc6 3.c3 d5 4.Bb5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3
{ This funky-looking move introduces the Ponziani.   White's idea is to conquer the center with d2-d4, which, of course, we are not going idly allow... }
3... d5
{ This is the most thematic central countermeasure. Black strikes in the middle before White can get d4 in.   Note that c3 will turn out to be a rather ugly move in many variations as it will greatly hinder the development of the White's queenside. }
4. Bb5
{ This popular move leads to very exciting tactical skirmishes where Black is always on top! }
4... dxe4 5. Nxe5 Qg5
{ This Queen sortie - unlike White's Qa4 - packs a serious punch!   Both White pieces along the 5th rank are loose and the g2 pawn is also hanging! }
6. Nxc6 Qxb5 7. Nd4 Qg5
{ And White has a miserable position. Black has the 2 Bishops, easy development, and central superiority.  To top it all, the natural  8.O-O  loses to  8...Bh3  , so White has no good way to guard g2! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Ponziani"]
[Black "2.Nf3 Nc6 3.c3 d5 4.Bb5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3
{ This funky-looking move introduces the Ponziani.   White's idea is to conquer the center with d2-d4, which, of course, we are not going idly allow... }
3... d5
{ This is the most thematic central countermeasure. Black strikes in the middle before White can get d4 in.   Note that c3 will turn out to be a rather ugly move in many variations as it will greatly hinder the development of the White's queenside. }
4. Bb5
{ This popular move leads to very exciting tactical skirmishes where Black is always on top! }
4... dxe4 5. Nxe5 Qg5
{ This Queen sortie - unlike White's Qa4 - packs a serious punch!   Both White pieces along the 5th rank are loose and the g2 pawn is also hanging! }
6. Qa4
{ The most popular choice both on club and master level but shockingly White is already in severe trouble! }
6... Qxg2
{ Whenever we take this pawn, the main idea is not to be a pawn ahead but to get closer to the white King! }
7. Bxc6+ bxc6 8. Qxc6+ Kd8
{ 9.Qxa8  Qxh1+  10.Ke2  Bd6!  11.Nxf7+  Kd7  12.Nxh8  Ba6+  With forced mate to follow.  This line demonstrates the main idea of the Queen's attack on g2: To demolish White's defenses on the light squares. }
9. Rf1 Bh3
{ The flashy style continues. In order to get to the white King we have to allow Qxa8 with check! }
10. Qxa8+ Ke7 11. Nc6+ Kf6 12. Qd8+ Kg6
{ And all White achieved is that now the black minor pieces can develop freely. }
