[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Ponziani"]
[Black "2.Nf3 Nc6 3.c3 d5 4.Qa4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3
{ This funky-looking move introduces the Ponziani.   White's idea is to conquer the center with d2-d4, which, of course, we are not going idly allow... }
3... d5
{ This is the most thematic central countermeasure. Black strikes in the middle before White can get d4 in.   Note that c3 will turn out to be a rather ugly move in many variations as it will greatly hinder the development of the White's queenside. }
4. Qa4 Bd7
{ Although f6 is the preferred method of the top GMs, such an ugly move can't be recommended in a course that prides itself on its sound principles 😊. }
5. exd5 Nd4
{ With this move we send the White Queen on another excursion, allowing us to pull ahead in development. }
6. Qd1 Nxf3+ 7. Qxf3 Nf6
{ Morphy would be rubbing his hands in glee! White has nothing developed and the c3 pawn adds insult to injury. }
8. c4 { Is an attempt to revive the b1 Knight as soon as possible. } 8... Bc5
9. Nc3 c6
{ Black needs to 'bite' into the center pawns in order to initiate a fight before White completes development. }
10. h3
{ White needs to eliminate the Bg4 threat before playing Be2.   To be fully honest, I find it insulting that Black here does not have a decisive lead, but sometimes the engines prove the ugliest moves the most resilient. }
10... O-O 11. Be2 cxd5 12. cxd5 Ne8
{ Speaking of not-so-aesthetic moves, this retreat seems to be the best to fight for an edge.   The idea is that in order to recover d5, Black would have to give up the Bishop @@StartBracket@@Bb4-Bxc3@@EndBracket@@.   Instead, we opt to reroute the Knight to the delicious d4 outpost and leave the doubled d-pawns alone. }
13. O-O Nd6 14. d3 Nf5
{ And Black has a preferable position.   Once the Knight lands on d4, we can launch the second wave of the attack with f7-f5. }
