{ This funky-looking move introduces the Ponziani.   White's idea is to conquer the center with d2-d4, which, of course, we are not going idly allow... }
3... d5
{ This is the most thematic central countermeasure. Black strikes in the middle before White can get d4 in.   Note that c3 will turn out to be a rather ugly move in many variations as it will greatly hinder the development of the White's queenside. }
4. Qa4 Bd7
{ Although f6 is the preferred method of the top GMs, such an ugly move can't be recommended in a course that prides itself on its sound principles 😊. }
5. exd5 Nd4
{ With this move we send the White Queen on another excursion, allowing us to pull ahead in development. }
6. Qd1 Nxf3+ 7. Qxf3 Nf6
{ Morphy would be rubbing his hands in glee! White has nothing developed and the c3 pawn adds insult to injury. }
8. Bc4 b5 9. Bb3 e4 10. Qe2 Bd6
{ Black's developing moves just play themselves, whereas White is walking a fine line. }
11. d4 O-O 12. Bg5
{ This is a vitally important move, otherwise Black gains a huge attack. }
12... h6 13. Bh4 g5
{ The pin is simply too annoying and so we don't compromise in eliminating it.   This operation, however, is NOT compromising the safety of our King as White has no means with which to attack it. }
14. Bg3 a5
{ We are channeling our inner Alekhine by playing across the whole board!   The idea is to kick the Bishop so we will gain access to the b2 pawn along the b-file. }
15. O-O a4 16. Bc2 Bg4 17. Qxb5 Rb8
{ This move reveals the point of the a5-a4 operation: The b2 pawn is up for grabs. }
18. Qxa4 Rxb2
{ And Black has tremendous compensation for the pawn. The main threat is Bd7, winning the c2 Bishop against which White only has token defenses.  The following line demonstrates Black's attacking potential splendidly:  19.Bb3  Be2  20.Re1  e3!!  this move rips the King's defenses apart  21.fxe3  Bxg3  22.hxg3  Qe7  and the Black attack breaks through. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6.1) Ponziani - Model Games"]
[Black "Zelic, Ml vs. Brkic, A., Split 2016"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 d5 4. Qa4 Bd7 5. exd5 Nd4 6. Qd1 Nxf3+ 7. Qxf3 Nf6 8.
Bc4 b5 { Brkic comes up with the good and plays the best moves in this line! }
9. Bb3 e4 10. Qe2 Bd6 11. d4 O-O 12. Bg5 h6 13. Bh4 a5
{ Our line goes with g5 first and then a5, but this is only a minor difference. }
14. Nd2 g5 15. Bg3 a4 16. Bc2 Bg4 { Brkic plays with perfect accuracy. } 17.
Qe3
{ 17.Qxb5  was the lesser evil, although even here, Black is better after the thematic:  17...Rb8  18.Qxa4  Rxb2  19.Rc1  Nxd5⩱ }
17... Nxd5
{ White is now forced to capture on e4, thus opening e-file against his own uncastled King... }
18. Qxe4 Nf6 19. Qe3 Nd5 20. Qe4 Re8 21. Be5
{ White is walking on very thin ice.... } 21... Nf6 22. Qe3 Nd7 23. Qe4
{ This is just too much, White is asking for trouble and Brkic delivers... }
23... f5 24. Qd5+ Kf8 25. O-O
{ It looks like White has managed to avoid the worst, but the tactical skirmish is just about to begin! }
25... Nxe5 26. dxe5 Rxe5 27. Qd4
{ 27.Qc6  Rb8  also leaves the white Queen in a delicate situation.... } 27...
c5 28. Qd3 Rd5 { This tactic wins a piece and with it the game too. } 29. Qe3
Bf4 { 29...Rxd2  was good too! } 30. Qe6 Rd6
{ And White can't avoid losing the d2 Knight and so he preferred to surrender.   A great game by the Croatian GM! }
*

