[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ This ambitious central break introduces the Scotch Game. } 3... exd4 4. c3
{ This move is an attempt to stir the game back to the Danish Gambit. } 4...
Nf6
{ Once again, to keep things simple, we kindly decline and instead aim for rapid development. }
5. e5 Nd5 6. cxd4 d6
{ Undermining the center in a fashion that is often seen in the Alapin Sicilian! }
7. Bc4 dxe5 8. dxe5 Nb6
{ This is a super tricky move to find, given that the natural alternative  8...Be6  looks very healthy.  The idea is that Black can exploit the far-advanced e5 pawn and the weak squares in the White camp after the Queen trade. }
9. Qxd8+ Nxd8 10. Bb3 Be6 11. Nbd2 Nc6 12. Bxe6 fxe6
{ Despite the split pawns, e5 is much more of a headache for White than e6 is for us. }
13. Ke2 O-O-O
{ And Black has a very comfortable game, ...Bc5 followed by ...Rhf8 could follow with annoying pressure. }
