[White "7) The Scotch Game"]
[Black "5.Nxc6 bxc6 6.e5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ This ambitious central break introduces the Scotch Game. } 3... exd4 4. Nxd4
Nf6
{ This alongside  4...Bc5  is the most thematic response. Black immediately challenges the e4-pawn. }
5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7
{ This is the main move in this position. Black's goal is to lure the white Queen to e2, creating a unique situation where both sides struggle to develop their Bishops. }
7. Qe2 Nd5 8. c4 Ba6
{ This move allows us to keep the Knight on d5, due to the pin, and it also prepares queenside castling. }
9. Nd2 O-O-O
{ Just like in the main line, here too, we prefer to accelerate our development by castling queenside! }
10. Qe4 { Is most popular, but inaccurate here! } 10... Nb6 11. b3 d5
{ Black is already better as taking en passant loses a piece on the e-file. }
12. cxd5 { 12.exd6??  Qxe4+  13.Nxe4  Re8  14.f3  f5-+ } 12... Bxf1 13. Rxf1
Rxd5
{ The best recapture because it conquers the d-file and threatens with the deadly Rxe5 as well. }
14. Bb2 Nd7
{ Black must play forcefully in order to delay/prevent White's castling. } 15.
Nf3 Nc5 { And the white King is stuck in the middle, Black stands better. } *

