1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ This ambitious central break introduces the Scotch Game. } 3... exd4 4. Nxd4
Nf6
{ This alongside  4...Bc5  is the most thematic response. Black immediately challenges the e4-pawn. }
5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7
{ This is the main move in this position. Black's goal is to lure the white Queen to e2, creating a unique situation where both sides struggle to develop their Bishops. }
7. Qe2 Nd5 8. c4 Ba6
{ This move allows us to keep the Knight on d5, due to the pin, and it also prepares queenside castling. }
9. Nd2 O-O-O
{ Just like in the main line, here too, we prefer to accelerate our development by castling queenside! }
10. b3 f6 11. Qe4 Nb6
{ We must move the Knight as now the Queen is out of the pin. } 12. Bb2 fxe5
13. Be2
{ White hopes to harmoniusly finish development and then exploit the awkward placement of our queenside pieces. }
13... Kb8
{ This is the key move. We want to break with d5 but in the tactical skirmish our Bishop would hang on a6 with a check! }
14. O-O d5
{ And the position is really messy. We have an extra pawn and a mighty pawn center but our pieces are poorly coordinated.   Our plan after a move like Qc2 is to play e4 and then extract the kingside pieces with Qf7 and Be7. }
