[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7 7. Qe2 Nd5 8.
c4 Ba6 9. b3 O-O-O 10. Bb2 f6 11. Nd2 fxe5 12. O-O-O Re8
{ This speculative variation is hardly the right approach against a GM of Sokolov's caliber. Black easily handles the pressure and comes out on top in the early middlegame. }
13. g3 Kb8
{ 13...Nf6  14.Bh3  Kb8  15.Nf3  d6  Was probably even more convincing. } 14.
Bg2 Qf7 15. Rhe1 Bb4
{ This final developing move also creates annoying threats around the c3 square. }
16. Ne4 Nb6
{ This retreat announces Black's plan B- to conquer the center with d7-d5. }
17. Bc3 Bxc3 18. Nxc3 d5
{ Black is comfortably ahead. Although the central pawns are under pressure, White does not have sufficient firepower to cause serious trouble. }
19. Qb2 e4 20. a4 Rhf8 21. a5
{ It seems that White manages to crack the pawn chain, but Black has a clever tactical countermeasure: }
21... Nd7 22. cxd5 Nc5
{ White will manage to eliminate the center, but only at a cost of an exchange. }
23. Nxe4 Nd3+ 24. Rxd3 Bxd3 25. dxc6 Bxe4 26. Rxe4 Rxe4 27. Bxe4 Qxf2
{ The dust has settled, and at the end of this massive skirmish, Black has emerged with an exchange up and a very much winnable endgame! Sokolov converts without any drama: }
28. Qxf2 Rxf2 29. Bxh7 Rxh2 30. Bf5 Ra2 31. g4 Rxa5 32. Kd2 Rb5 33. Be6 a5 34.
Kd3 Ka7 35. Kd4 Kb6 36. Bd5 Rb4+ *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7.1) The Scotch Game - Model Games"]
[Black "Smeets, Jan vs. Adams, Michael, London 2008"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7 7. Qe2 Nd5 8.
c4 Ba6 9. b3 O-O-O 10. Bb2 Qg5 11. Qf3
{ This move demonstrates how tricky this line is. Even a 2600 GM gets lost in the jungle of these messy Scotch lines.   11.Nd2  Is best, as per our main line. }
11... Bb4+
{ Adams errs too! Better would have been:  11...Nb4!  12.Na3  Bc5  13.Be2  d6  14.exd6  Rxd6  15.O-O  Kb8  16.Rad1  Re8⩱  and Black's piece activity prevails. }
12. Kd1 Nf4 13. h4 Qh6 14. g3 Ne6 15. Bc1 Qg6
{ Adams opts for a tactical resolution, but the more ambitious g5 was better!   15...g5  16.hxg5  Qf8  17.Be3  d5!  With total chaos on the board. I certainly prefer Black though as the White king seems to be an easy-to-target to play against! }
16. h5 Qc2+ { This clever pseudo-sac was the idea behind Qg6. } 17. Kxc2 Nd4+
18. Kd3
{ A very strange move that exposes the White king unnecessarily.   18.Kb2  Nxf3  19.Be2  Nd4   19...Nxe5??  20.f4  20.Bg4  c5  With a royal mess, although the engine prefers White here. }
18... Nxf3 19. Ke4
{ Smeets is chasing a dream. The King is madly running after the Knight while the entire white army is idly sitting at home. It is a perfect recepie for disaster! }
19... Nxe5
{ 19...c5  Was also very good! Adams instead prefers to hurt White on the other diagonal. }
20. h6 { 20.Kxe5  Be7∓ } 20... Ng4 21. hxg7 Rhg8 22. Kf5
{ It really feels like Smeets is going for a self mate... } 22... Rxg7 23. f3
Nf2 24. Rh2 Bc5 25. Bh6 Rg6 26. Nd2 Bd4
{ This move seals the deal. White has to leave the Rook en prise. } 27. Bg5
{ 27.Re1  Rf6+  28.Kg5  Rg8+  29.Kh5  Rf5+  30.Kh4  Bf6+  Leads to a quick mate. }
27... Re8 28. Rxf2 Re5+
{ And White gave up.   28...Re5+  29.Kf4  Rgxg5  And there is way too much 'hanging'. }
