[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d4
{ This move steers the game to the Scotch Gambit. } 4... exd4 5. e5
{ This is actually my recommendation in my Beginners e4 course, so now I will have to reveal my darkest secrets... }
5... d5 6. Bb5 Ne4 7. Nxd4 Bd7
{ Although Bc5 is also a possibility here, I consider Bd7 to be the simpler way to end up in the same position. }
8. Bxc6 bxc6
{ This trade gives a special character to the position. We have the Bishop pair, but our structure is a bit compromised due to the doubled c-pawns.   The most important strategic goal for us now is to avoid White creating a blockade on the c5 square. }
9. O-O Bc5 10. f3
{ This is exactly the move I recommend in the Beginners 1.e4 course so we have to tackle this first. }
10... Ng5 11. f4 Ne4 12. Be3 Bb6
{ In my opinion, this is the most exciting way to play for Black as now the c6-c5 progression will create a fluid central pawn formation for Black.   This means that White's main strategic goal, the blockade on c5 has been dealt with! }
13. Nd2 c5 14. N4f3 Nxd2 15. Qxd2 Bf5
{ With a complicated position where both sides have their chances. We look to castle next and then secure the center with c6- Qe7 Rad8 etc. }
