[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) The Scotch Gambit"]
[Black "3.Bc4 Nf6 4.d4 exd4 5.O-O #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d4
{ This move steers the game to the Scotch Gambit. } 4... exd4 5. O-O
{ This move offers another pawn.   At first sight, it may look dangerous to accept, but in reality, the disappearance of the White center reduces White's attacking potential. }
5... Nxe4 6. Nc3
{ This ridiculous move is the so-called Nakhmanson Gambit.   It is virtually losing by force, but like all shady gambits, we need to treat it with a hint of caution. }
6... Nxc3
{ Although dxc3 is also winning, that variation leads to a line with our King on f6, something I would rather avoid... }
7. bxc3 d5
{ Easy does it! Simply playing healthy developing moves, we can pull ahead comfortably. }
8. Bd3 Be7 9. cxd4 O-O
{ And Black stands much better, we have an extra pawn and White has nothing to show for it.   We look to complete development with Bg4 and Qd7. }
