1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d4
{ This move steers the game to the Scotch Gambit. } 4... exd4 5. O-O
{ This move offers another pawn.   At first sight, it may look dangerous to accept, but in reality, the disappearance of the White center reduces White's attacking potential. }
5... Nxe4 6. Re1 d5 { This move ensures that White can't win a piece on e4. }
7. Bxd5
{ White's only move to keep the attack going and to recover one of the sacrificed pawns. }
7... Qxd5 8. Nc3 Qh5
{ The other big theoretical line is  8...Qa5  , but the text leads to easier positions for Black. }
9. Nxe4 Be6
{ This developing move is very handy as it also shields the King from the discovered checks. }
10. Bg5
{ The best move for White, which, annoyingly, stops us from queenside castling. }
10... Bd6
{ Although this move allows White to mess up our pawn structure, the doubled d-pawns prove to be surprisingly difficult to target! }
11. Bf6
{ This is a cheeky trick, hoping for the royal fork. The refutation is a counter-tactic! }
11... Bxh2+ 12. Nxh2 Qxd1 13. Raxd1 gxf6 14. Nxf6+ Kf8 15. g4 h5
{ This is definitely a cute one to remember! Once again, we solve our troubles by tactical means. }
16. g5
{ After  16.gxh5  Kg7∓  Black regains the pawn with a favorable ending.   16.Nxh5  Bxg4!  ∓ is the tactical justification behind the ...h5 idea. Black is simply a pawn up. }
16... Rd8
{ Black is a pawn to the good. Our plan is to blockade with ...Ne7-f5 followed by ...Kg7. }
