[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8.1) The Scotch Gambit - Model Games"]
[Black "Von Bahr, O. vs. Holm, Kristian Stuvik, Fagernes 2018"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. e5 d5 6. Bb5 Ne4 7. Nxd4 Bd7 8.
Bxc6 bxc6 9. O-O Bc5 10. f3 Ng5 11. f4 Ne4 12. Be3 Bb6 13. Nd2 c5 14. N4f3 Nxd2
15. Qxd2 Bf5
{ This is where our theory ends and the subsequent play is hugely instructive! }
16. c4 dxc4
{ This is a vitally important concept in this setup. Instead of accepting the rigid structure with d5-d4 where the Bishops would have less scope.   In contrast, now our light square Bishop becomes a hero, and the wrecked pawn structure becomes far less important. }
17. Rac1 O-O 18. Qf2 Qe7
{ This move both clears the d-file for the eventual Rfd8 and adds a defender to the c5 pawn. }
19. Nd2 Bd3 20. Rfe1 Qe6 21. Bxc5 Rfd8
{ Black's strategy has proven triumphant. The White army is too passive to take advantage of the positional gains and the d3 Bishop has a powerful restricting effect. }
22. Ne4
{ 22.b3  Was White's only move.  22...Ba5  23.b4  Bb6  With a messy battle where Black has the better chances. }
22... Qc6 23. Bxb6 axb6
{ Having fixed the pawn structure, Black is now definitely in the driver's seat. }
24. Nc3 Bf5
{ At this point the game becomes a little bit topsy-turvy. Black's cleanest plan should be to play for b5-b4. }
25. Rcd1 Rd3 26. Qh4 Re8 27. h3 h6 28. Kh2 Qc5 29. Qh5 Bc8 30. Qh4 Qd4 31. Re4
Rxd1 32. Rxd4 Rxd4
{ For a human mind the attacking idea of Bb7 followed by Rd2, seems unstoppable, at least in the longer run, but the engine still claims some chances for White. }
33. Nb5
{ The decisive error! Qf2 was imperative with the idea of holding the 2nd rank. }
33... Rd2 34. Qe1 Rxb2 35. Nxc7 Bb7 { Now it is all over! } 36. h4 Rxg2+ 37.
Kh3 Rd8 38. h5 Rd3+ 39. Kh4 Rh2+ 40. Kg4 Bf3+ 41. Kg3 Rg2+
{ And White gave up before the inevitable checkmate! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) Two Knights"]
[Black "3.Bc4 Nf6 4.Nc3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6
{ Note that we will transpose after  4.d4  , which we already examined in the Scotch Gambit chapterhere. }
4. Nc3
{ This natural but very questionable move is one of the most popular ones on club level and so we need to deal with this thoroughly! }
4... Nxe4
{ This move is by far the best. A lot of people shy away from it because of the Bxf7 possibility, which is actually White's worst way to respond! }
5. Bxf7+
{ Although this move has the appeal of denying Black's castling rights, in reality this is a poor choice as it gives up both the center and the Bishop pair. }
5... Kxf7 6. Nxe4 d5
{ The Black center is terrifying and it is easy to see that White simply does not have the means to get to the black King. }
7. Neg5+ Kg8
{ The black King is perfectly safe here and we are already threatening to win a piece with e4. The Knights have nowhere to run... }
8. d3 h6 9. Nh3 Bg4
{ The pin is super annoying as White can't attack the Bishop and also is unable to block the pin!   If White manages to avoid the pending disaster with e5-e4, we look to develop with Qf6, Bd6, Kh7, and Rf8 }
