[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6
{ Note that we will transpose after  4.d4  , which we already examined in the Scotch Gambit chapterhere. }
4. Nc3
{ This natural but very questionable move is one of the most popular ones on the club level and so we need to deal with this thoroughly! }
4... Nxe4
{ This move is by far the best. A lot of people shy away from it because of the Bxf7 possibility, which is actually White's worst way to respond! }
5. O-O
{ This is an attempt to turn the game into a 'reverse Stafford Gambit'. Considering the popularity of the regular version of this shady gambit, we certainly want to consider the tempo-up version! }
5... Nxc3 6. dxc3 f6
{ This remarkably ugly move is actually the best way to fight for an advantage. The idea is to secure the e5 pawn and also deny the Ng5 threat. }
7. Re1 d6 8. h3 Qd7
{ This peculiar idea was played by fellow Chessable author 'Kaldas90' AKA Kamil Plichta, and indeed this is the way to secure our edge! }
9. a4 Nd8 10. b4 Nf7 11. Ba3 Be7
{ Black has resolved all his problems and stood clearly better! } *

