[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6
{ Note that we will transpose after  4.d4  , which we already examined in the Scotch Gambit chapterhere. }
4. d3
{ This quiet continuation is super trendy nowadays against both the Italian and the Two Knights. }
4... Be7
{ In turn, I recommend we continue with a quiet-looking move of our own.   This move, however, can be surprisingly tricky and aggressive! Our idea is to play for an early d5 break, and often aim for Marshall Gambit-like positions. }
5. O-O
{ This move is the most flexible as White now can still continue with both c3 or Nc3. }
5... O-O 6. Re1
{ This move is the most annoying as now d5 is no longer possible. } 6... d6
{ This move may look passive, but in fact, we do intend a central expansion right away.   Also, note that we are now threatening to grab the Bishop pair with Na5. }
7. c3 Na5
{ This move introduces the aforementioned expansion. Our plan is to play c7-c5. }
8. Bb5
{ This is White's only measure to retain the Bishop. The text allows Black to expand freely on the queenside and in the center. }
8... a6 9. Ba4 b5 10. Bc2 c5
{ With some curious detours we arrived in the d3 variation of the Ruy Lopez, which is considered to be harmless. }
11. Nbd2 Nc6
{ The Knight has fulfilled its duty and now returns to the middle. } 12. Nf1 h6
{ The bunny ear is a necessary preparation for Be6, as it denies Ng5. } 13. Ng3
Be6 14. h3 Rc8
{ The text denies White's central ambitions associated with the d4 break.   White is now struggling to find a good follow-up, as the natural Be3 is strongly met by the thematic d6-d5 break, which is one of our main plans in this structure. }
15. Be3
{ After  15.d4?  cxd4  16.cxd4  exd4  White can't retake due to the hanging Bishop on c2! }
15... d5
{ And Black takes over the initiative. We plan to push d4 and then even c5-c4, grabbing more space. }
