1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6
{ Note that we will transpose after  4.d4  , which we already examined in the Scotch Gambit chapterhere. }
4. d3
{ This quiet continuation is super trendy nowadays against both the Italian and the Two Knights. }
4... Be7
{ In turn, I recommend we continue with a quiet-looking move of our own.   This move, however, can be surprisingly tricky and aggressive! Our idea is to play for an early d5 break, and often aim for Marshall Gambit-like positions. }
5. O-O
{ This move is the most flexible as White now can still continue with both c3 or Nc3. }
5... O-O 6. Nc3 d6 7. a4 { As usual, White needs to prepare for Na5. } 7... Be6
{ Our bread and butter... } 8. Re1 Nb4
{ This is actually my own novelty in this well-known theoretical position, the most popular  8...Qd7  is well met by  9.Nd5  with annoying consequences.  The idea behind Nb4 is to pave the way for the usual c7-c5 expansion and it also nicely supports the d5 square. }
9. Bxe6 fxe6 10. d4
{ This is the most logical response to Black's abandonment of the center, but even this move does not cause us any problems. }
10... exd4 11. Nxd4 Qd7
{ Having secured the tender underbelly of the position, we now look to expand with c5 followed by d5, counterpunching in the center.   The position is level, but I prefer Black as our plan is quite energetic and straightforward. }
*

