1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6
{ Note that we will transpose after  4.d4  , which we already examined in the Scotch Gambit chapterhere. }
4. d3
{ This quiet continuation is super trendy nowadays against both the Italian and the Two Knights. }
4... Be7
{ In turn, I recommend we continue with a quiet-looking move of our own.   This move, however, can be surprisingly tricky and aggressive! Our idea is to play for an early d5 break, and often aim for Marshall Gambit-like positions. }
5. O-O
{ This move is the most flexible as White now can still continue with both c3 or Nc3. }
5... O-O 6. c3
{ This is most popular on club level, but it is not really that great. } 6...
d5
{ This is our main idea!   We break the center when White is the least prepared, having just played a meaningless c2-c3. }
7. exd5 Nxd5 8. Re1 Bg4
{ The key move. This pin ensures that our e5 pawn is solidly defended. } 9. h3
Bh5 10. g4
{ Is just too irresponsible. Black's initiative will easily outweigh the value of a single pawn. }
10... Bg6 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. Rxe5 c6
{ Black has a very promising attack, the White king has been drastically weakened and the White queenside is yet to be developed. }
13. Bxd5 Bd6 { This awesome zwischenzug is a key idea! } 14. Re1 cxd5
{ And Black's incoming Qh4 followed by f7-f5 will be decisive! } *

