[White "9) Two Knights"]
[Black "4.Ng5 d5 5.exd5 b5 6.Bxb5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6
{ Note that we will transpose after  4.d4  , which we already examined in the Scotch Gambit chapterhere. }
4. Ng5
{ This move steers the game towards the variation known as the Fried Liver, just to add another example to the list of openings that were not exactly named with too much thought in mind... }
4... d5 { This is Black's only way to shield the f7-pawn. } 5. exd5 b5
{ This is a cheeky, daring, and most importantly, fun variation. The idea is to sacrifice a pawn in order to pull ahead in development and central control, a common goal in many of our lines.   Lately, the biggest main line with  5...Na5  has grown immensely, and its theory has become both very deep and dense so I thought it best to avoid it. }
6. Bxb5
{ This is a less accurate move here!   6.Bf1  is the main move, which protects the g2-pawn in case Black plays ...Qxd5, allowing White the immediate Nc3. }
6... Qxd5 7. Nc3 { This move allowes us to regain the material instantly. }
7... Qxg2 8. Qf3 Qxf3 9. Nxf3
{ This queenless middlegame is slightly preferable for Black due to our space advantage in the center. }
9... Bd7 10. d3 Nd4
{ This maneuver ensures that Black gains some space in the center after the inevitable trades. }
11. Bxd7+ Kxd7 12. Nxd4 exd4 13. Ne2 Re8
{ And Black's position is slightly better due to the better piece coordination.   We will stabilize the center with c7-c5, and then complete development with Bd6. }
*

