[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6
{ Note that we will transpose after  4.d4  , which we already examined in the Scotch Gambit chapterhere. }
4. Ng5
{ This move stirs the game towards the variation known as the Fried Liver, just to add another example to the list of openings that were not exactly named with too much thought in mind... }
4... d5 { This is Black's only way to shield the f7-pawn. } 5. exd5 b5
{ This is a cheeky, daring, and most importantly, fun variation. The idea is to sacrifice a pawn in order to pull ahead in development and central control, a common goal in many of our lines.   Lately, the biggest main line with  5...Na5  has grown immensely, and its theory has become both very deep and dense so I thought it best to avoid it. }
6. Bxb5
{ This is a less accurate move here!   6.Bf1  is the main move, which protects the g2-pawn in case Black plays ...Qxd5, allowing White the immediate Nc3. }
6... Qxd5 7. Bxc6+
{ This move surrenders the bishop pair and as such, it has to be questionable. The resulting lines are extremely wild and fun! Be ready for some serious sac-fest! }
7... Qxc6 8. O-O Bb7 9. Qf3 e4 10. Qb3
{ This position is very similar to the 8.Qb3 lines and here too, we go for broke! }
10... O-O-O
{ Not only do we not care about Nxf7 but we even allow it to be a fork! } 11.
Qh3+ { 11.Nxf7?  e3!  12.f3  e2  13.Re1  Bc5+  is crushing. } 11... Kb8 12.
Nxf7 Rd5
{ This rook-lift is the key idea. Black's attack is extremely dangerous, especially since the white queenside is a mere observer of the events! }
13. Nxh8 { Demonstrates the dangers lurking around: } 13... Rh5 14. Qb3 Bc5 15.
Nc3 e3 16. f3 e2+ { And it's all over. } *

