1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6
{ Note that we will transpose after  4.d4  , which we already examined in the Scotch Gambit chapterhere. }
4. Ng5
{ This move steers the game towards the variation known as the Fried Liver, just to add another example to the list of openings that were not exactly named with too much thought in mind... }
4... d5 { This is Black's only way to shield the f7-pawn. } 5. exd5 b5
{ This is a cheeky, daring, and most importantly, fun variation. The idea is to sacrifice a pawn in order to pull ahead in development and central control, a common goal in many of our lines.   Lately, the biggest main line with  5...Na5  has grown immensely, and its theory has become both very deep and dense so I thought it best to avoid it. }
6. Bf1 Nxd5
{ This move introduces our main idea.   The line has long been known but we hope to turn around some of the old@@StartBracket@@er@@EndBracket@@ evaluations! }
7. Bxb5 Bb7 8. d4
{ White's most ambitious and aggressive move, that defends the Knight on g5 and challenges the center at the same time.   Now the game becomes very sharp and any mistake may be the last one for both sides! }
8... exd4 9. O-O Be7 10. Qh5 g6 11. Qh6
{ White denies our castling and also introduces Qg7 as a potential threat. }
11... Qd7
{ Black prepares for queenside castling, further contributing to the irrational complications in the position. }
12. Qg7 { Is well met by the thematic: } 12... O-O-O 13. Qxf7
{ Or  13.Nxf7??  Bf6  and Black wins a piece and an easy game! } 13... Rhf8
{ Amazingly, forcing a queen trade is still beneficial to us, depsite the small material deficit. }
14. Qxh7
{ Lets the Genie out of the bottle. Black grabs the initiative with gusto! }
14... Nf4 15. Bxf4 Rxf4 16. Nf3 Rxf3 { Such moves are simply mandatory. } 17.
gxf3
{ White's king's defense has been blasted open and the invaders are quick to jump onto their defenseless prey. }
17... Qf5 18. Bd3 Qxf3 19. Nd2 Ne5
{ A truly stunning conclusion. White loses material: } 20. Nxf3 Nxf3+ 21. Kh1
Ng5+ 22. f3 Nxh7 23. Bxg6 Ng5
{ And Black stands much better with a raging attack and superior piece mobility. }
