[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. Ng5 d5 5. exd5 b5 6. Bf1 Nxd5 7. Bxb5 Bb7 8.
d4 exd4 9. O-O Be7 10. Nf3
{ This move causes no difficulty, instead our main line is Qh5. } 10... O-O 11.
c3
{ White can't afford such a lackluster playstyle in this variation. Both Re1 and Nxd4 would have been better. Black now grabs the lead. }
11... dxc3 12. Nxc3 Ncb4 13. Nxd5 Nxd5
{ The surprising Qxd5 was better here!   13...Qxd5!  14.Qxd5  Bxd5  15.Be3  Rfb8  16.Ba4  Bf6  With noticeable pressure on the queenside pawns. }
14. Bd2 Bd6 { Ponkratov begins a kingside attack } 15. Qc2 Qf6 16. Ng5 Qh6
{ This is a very clever move. White is forced to play the 'ugly' g3. } 17. g3
{ 17.h3  Bf4!  18.Nf3  Bxd2  19.Nxd2  Nf4  And the white kingside collapses! }
17... Be7 18. h4 Bxg5 19. hxg5 Nb4
{ The right idea but the wrong execution.   19...Ne3  Was the way to go, which disallows White's clever counterpunch. }
20. gxh6
{ White returns the favor.   20.Qe4!!  This incredible move throws a spanner in the works, now White is off the hook!  20...Bxe4  21.gxh6  With a better version of the game from White's point of view. }
20... Nxc2
{ In contrast to the above variation, here White's a1 is hanging, and the retreat of the Knight with Nd4 also threatens with deadly threats! }
21. hxg7 Rfd8 22. Bc3
{ White gives up the exchange, hoping that the two Bishops and the g7 pawn provide sufficient counterplay.    Ponkratov converts in an impressive fashion, but since this is out of the scope of the course, I provide the rest without commentary. }
22... Nxa1 23. Rxa1 Bf3 24. Re1 Rd1 25. Rxd1 Bxd1 26. f4 Bg4 27. Kf2 Rd8 28.
Ke3 Rd6 29. Be5 Rb6 30. a4 c5 31. Bc4 Rg6 32. Bd3 Rh6 33. a5 Bc8 34. Bc4 Be6
35. Bb5 Rg6 36. Kf2 f6 37. Bd6 Rxg7 38. a6 c4 39. Bc6 Bc8 40. Bb5 Be6 41. Bc6
f5 42. Bb8 c3 43. bxc3 Bc4 44. Bb7 Rg6 45. Bxa7 Bxa6 46. Bd5+ Kf8 47. c4 Bc8
