[White "9.1) Two Knights - Model Games"]
[Black "Rodriguez Vila, Andres vs. Filippov, Anton, Istanbul 2012"]
[Result "*"]

{ Please note that this game starts off as a 'proper' Italian, but with a transposition on move 11 we will enter our main line. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d3 O-O 6. O-O d5 7. exd5 Nxd5 8.
Re1 Bg4 9. h3 Bh5 10. Nbd2 Nb6 11. Bb5 Bd6
{ This is our theoretical position in out Be7 line, the only difference being that in our line the Bishop goes to d6 from e7, rather than from c5. }
12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. Ne4 f5
{ Fillipov plays the game in a very aggressive spirit, the right way to go as far as I am concerned! }
14. Ng3 Bxf3 15. Qxf3 Qd7 16. c4 Rae8 17. b3 c5
{ Although objectively not best, this move is strategically justified. Black wants to seal the center before launching a kingside onslaught.   17...Bc5  Is the preference of the mighty machine. }
18. Bb2 Qf7 19. Re2 Re6
{ Filippov reroutes all his pieces to the kingside, where he intends to carry out a decisive operation. }
20. Rae1 Nd7 21. Qb7 g5 22. Nf1 h5
{ I love how consistent and uncompromising Black's play is! This is the chessboard representation of the  'pedal to the metal' concept!   The engine is less enthused, but for humans to defend an onslaught like this is a hugely unpleasant task! }
23. f3 Qh7 24. Qxa7 Rg6 25. Qb7 g4 26. fxg4 hxg4 27. hxg4 Rxg4
{ Black's attack is gaining more and more momentum. } 28. Rf2 f4 29. Qd5+ Rf7
30. Rf3 Kf8 31. Re2 Rfg7 32. Qe4 Qh5 33. Ne3 R4g5 34. Qa8+
{ Finally, White trembles under the immense pressure,  34.Nd5  was better. }
34... Kf7 35. Qd5+ Ke7 36. Nf1 Nf6 37. Qc6 Rh7
{ The attack is now irresistible. } 38. Kf2 Qh4+ 39. g3 fxg3+ 40. Nxg3 Rxg3
{ A nice touch to finish off a lovely attack. } 41. Rxe5+
{ 41.Rxg3  Ng4+  42.Kf3  Rf7+  43.Ke4  Rf4+  44.Kd5  Nf6  Would have been an epic way to finish! }
41... Bxe5 42. Qxc5+ Bd6 43. Bxf6+ Qxf6
{ A cute cross pin concludes this awesome game, a fitting finish! } *

