1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d3 Be7 5. O-O O-O 6. h3 d6 7. Nc3
{ We have reached one of the most popular positions in this line. In my mind, h3 @@StartBracket@@which normally arises with a slight difference: White plays Nc3 first and then h3@@EndBracket@@  is simply an illogical move as it allows us to grab the Bishop pair. }
7... Na5 8. a4 Nxc4 9. dxc4 Be6
{ In my opinion Black has the better practical chances already! } 10. b3 a5 11.
Bg5 Nd7
{ Although this move allows White to trade Bishops, thus eliminating the Bishop pair. However, Nd7 also prepares the f7-f5 break, immediately handing a long-lasting initiative to Black. }
12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13. Nd5 Bxd5 14. Qxd5
{ 14.cxd5  f5  Is a textbook case of a position where Black has the initiative and the only meaningful plan @@StartBracket@@attack on the kingside, along the f-file@@EndBracket@@. }
14... Nc5 15. Rfe1 Rad8 16. Rad1 Kh8
{ Again, Black prepares f5, and White has no obvious counter measures. } 17.
Re2 b6 18. Nd2 Qe6
{ A painful blunder, most likely due to the short time control.   18...Ne6!  Would have won on the spot, due to the dual threat of Nf4 and Nd4. }
19. Nb1 Qxd5 20. cxd5 f5
{ Despite the absence of the Queens, Black still does well with this break. }
21. exf5 Rxf5 22. Nc3 h5 23. Ne4 h4 24. Nxc5 bxc5 25. Re4 g5
{ This is a hugely instructive ending. Seemingly White has the better pawn structure, but the opposite is true! The semi-open b and f-files and a potential c5-c4 push means that Black is ahead. }
26. f3 Rb8 27. Rd3 Kg7 28. Kf2 Rf4 { Black plays an inspired ending. } 29. Rde3
Kf6 30. Ke2 Rb4 31. Rxb4 Rxb4 32. Re4 Rb6 33. Kd3 Kf5 34. Rc4 c6
{ This break opens the floodgates. The central pawn mass decides the game! }
35. dxc6 Rxc6 36. Re4 d5 37. Re2 Rb6 38. Kc3 Kf4 39. Rd2 Rd6 40. Re2 Rd8 41.
Kd3 Rb8 42. Kc3 Rb4 43. Rd2 d4+ 44. Kd3 c4+ 45. bxc4 Rxa4 46. Re2 Ra3+ 47. Kd2
Rc3 48. Re4+ Kf5 49. Re1 Rxc4 50. Rb1 Rb4 51. Ra1 a4 52. Kd3 Kf4 53. Ke2 Rc4
54. Kd3 Rc3+ 55. Kd2 a3 56. Ke2 Rxc2+ *

