1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4
{ This move introduces the Four Knights Scotch, whereas  4.Bb5  is the Four Knights Spanish. }
4... exd4 5. Nxd4 Bb4
{ Black immediately begins the battle for the middle, e4 is now hanging. } 6.
Nxc6 bxc6 7. Bd3 d5
{ Black immediately challenges the center and sets about utilizing the doubled c-pawns. }
8. exd5 O-O
{ Along with  8...cxd5  this is the other main line.  I chose this variation as  8...cxd5  exclusively leads to dull and structurally slightly inferior positions. In contrast, the text allows White far more opportunities to make a mistake. }
9. dxc6 Re8+ { Black now gets a tonne of play for the sacrificed material. }
10. Be2 Nd5 11. O-O Bxc3 { And Black wins a piece: } 12. bxc3 Nxc3 13. Qxd8
Nxe2+ 14. Kh1 Rxd8 { And the game. } *

