1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5
{ This move is the Four Knights Spanish, a variation that is played very rarely on club level. }
4... Nd4
{ I chose this move because, contrary to the other mainline with Bb4, it allows Black many fun and exciting positions. }
5. Nxd4
{ This is the most popular move on club level, which actually leads to a drawish ending if played well by White! }
5... exd4 6. Ne2
{ This mistake is actually the top choice on club level and is great news as this allows us to grab the initiative right away! }
6... c6 7. Bd3 d5 { Centah! Black is already taking charge. } 8. exd5 Qxd5
{ Bringing the Queen out is perfectly fine here as it can't be harassed by White minor pieces. }
9. O-O Bd6
{ This move puts the Bishop on the optimal diagonal for a kingside attack and also denies Nf4. }
10. Ng3 O-O
{ Black has a sensational position with more space, better piece mobility, and a developing kingside attack.   One of our strongest follow-ups here is the hyper-aggressive h5 with the idea of a rapid kingside attack! }
