1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5
{ This move is the Four Knights Spanish, a variation that is played very rarely on club level. }
4... Nd4
{ I chose this move because, contrary to the other mainline with Bb4, it allows Black many fun and exciting positions. }
5. Nxe5
{ This capture leads to a wild and rather irrational variation, where utmost precision is required from both sides to avoid immediate catastrophe. }
5... Qe7
{ This is the accurate move order here as  5...Nxb5  first would have allowed White to attack the c7 pawn after  6.Nxb5 }
6. f4 Nxb5 7. Nxb5 d6
{ Black now regains the pawn, but instead of balance, the position is about to get completely irrational. }
8. Nf3 Qxe4+ 9. Kf2
{ White voluntarily surrenders castling rights in order to access the e-file as soon as possible!   Identifying the hunter and the hunted is very tricky in this wild line! }
9... Ng4+ 10. Kg3
{ White must continue the crazy King walk, but Black has plenty to worry about too: The e-file pin and the check on c7 are both very concerning! }
10... Qg6 11. Nh4 Qf6 12. h3
{ White has to find a long streak of only moves in order to survive this King excursion. }
12... g5 13. Qe2+ Ne5
{ This sensational move is key in this wild line.   Since we are still threatening with Qxf4 mate, we can hang any piece... }
14. Nf3 gxf4+ 15. Kh2 Kd8
{ The tables have turned a little bit: Our King has lost its castling rights, while the White King, at long last, has found a safe spot on h2.   All this, however, comes at a cost for White: Black has the two Bishops and an extra pawn. }
16. d4 Ng6 17. Re1 Bd7
{ Defending the mate and hitting the b5 Knight.   Black's chances are preferable as we are very close to consolidating with Bg7 and then Re8 after which all endgames will heavily favor us. }
*

