1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5
{ This move is the Four Knights Spanish, a variation that is played very rarely on club level. }
4... Nd4
{ I chose this move because, contrary to the other mainline with Bb4, it allows Black many fun and exciting positions. }
5. Ba4 c6
{ This move may look a bit weird at first but it is a useful one!   First of all, the d-pawn has been unpinned and we are threatening at an opportune moment to hassle the Bishop with b7-b5 and then a5-a4. }
6. Nxe5 d6 7. Nf3 Bg4
{ This pin, combined with the fact that the a4 Bishop can't help to cover the kingside light squares, provides enough compensation for the sacrificed pawn. }
8. d3 d5
{ Black immediately strikes at the center and also extends the scope of the f8 Bishop. Morphian chess at its finest! }
9. exd5 Nxd5 10. O-O Be7
{ It is necessary to cover the e-file, in order to shield the King from Re1+. }
11. Re1 O-O 12. Nxd5 cxd5 13. c3 Nxf3+ 14. gxf3 Bf5
{ And Black has solid chances to play for a win, due to our better development and White's damaged pawn structure in front of the King. }
*

