1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5
{ This move is the Four Knights Spanish, a variation that is played very rarely on club level. }
4... Nd4
{ I chose this move because, contrary to the other mainline with Bb4, it allows Black many fun and exciting positions. }
5. Bc4 Bc5
{ These sacrificial ideas are common in the Nd4 variation, which is precisely why I picked it.   In general, the idea is to let go of the e5 pawn and use the tempi White spends on capturing it to create an attack. }
6. O-O { This move avoids confrontations but also promises little for White. }
6... d6 7. h3 { A sad necessity against the annoying ...Bg4 pin. } 7... c6 8.
d3 b5 9. Bb3 a5 10. a3 Nxb3
{ And Black stands slightly better with the bishop pair. We should follow up with ...O-O. If d3-d4 hits, we exchange on d4 once followed by ...Bd7. }
