[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 Nd4 5. Nxe5
{ This is a tricky variation, so I decided to back your knowledge with an 'anchor game' for this line. }
5... Qe7 6. f4 Nxb5 7. Nxb5 d6 8. Nf3 Qxe4+ 9. Kf2 Ng4+ 10. Kg3 Qg6 11. Nh4 Qf6
12. h3 g5 13. Qe2+ Ne5
{ Svidler is playing the best moves and now his opponent plays an inferior move: }
14. d4 { 14.Nf3  is best, as per our line. } 14... gxf4+ 15. Kh2 Qxh4 16. dxe5
Qg3+ 17. Kg1
{ With perfect play, Svidler pulls ahead, but now, at crucial junction, he drops the ball... }
17... f3
{ This move lets White off the hook.  Instead, the bold  17...Kd8  was necessary, with an obscure follow-up:  18.exd6  Bd7!!  this must have been the move that Svidler missed  19.dxc7+  Kc8  and amazingly, White has no meaningful way to stop Bc5+, with decisive effects.  E.g.  20.a4  Bc5+  21.Kf1  Re8  22.Qd2  Bxb5+  23.axb5  f3!  and the silicone monster announces mate in 5! }
18. Qxf3 { The game fizzles out into a basic draw. } 18... Qxf3 19. gxf3 Kd7
20. exd6 Bxd6 21. Nxd6 Kxd6 { And the players shook hands... } *

