[Black "Ponomariov, Ruslan vs. Almasi, Zoltan, Pamplona 1996"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 Nd4 5. Ba4 c6 6. Nxe5 d6 7. Nf3 Bg4 8. h3
{ Oddly, Ponomariov makes a very early mistake. The correct move is d3, as per our theory. }
8... Bxf3 9. gxf3 g6
{ Almasi finds the most dynamic setup, which allows him to play a Morphyesque middlegame. }
10. Nb1
{ A super ugly move that begs to be punished. Ponomariov hopes to kick the Knight with c2-c3 but this is just too passive. }
10... Qa5 11. c3 Nxf3+
{ This very clever tactic restores material balance, while Black keeps all his attacking trumps. }
12. Qxf3 Qxa4 13. d4
{ 13.Qxf6  Qxe4+  and Black will take on h1 with a check! } 13... Bg7 14. O-O
O-O 15. Bg5 Nh5
{ Almasi keeps his foot on the accelerator. Black is inviting Be7, which would further delay White's development. }
16. Be7 Rfe8 17. Bxd6 Rad8
{ Black plays simple, yet beautiful chess. The fully deployed army gives a very strong and intimidating impression. }
18. b3 Qa6 19. Bh2 c5 20. d5 f5
{ Stunning chess. Black keeps on hitting the iron while it's hot and Ponomariov has no time to consolidate. }
21. exf5 Rf8 22. d6 Rxf5 23. Qe3 Qc6 24. Re1 Bf8 25. Rd1 Re8 26. Qd2 Nf6
{ An unfortunate mistake. Instead, the spectacular Qf3 would have been terminal:  26...Qf3  27.d7  Re2  28.Qxe2  Qxe2  29.d8=Q  Qxf2+  30.Kh1  Qf3+  31.Kg1  Ng3!  32.Bxg3  Qxg3+  33.Kh1  Qxh3+  34.Kg1  Qg3+  35.Kh1  Rh5+  36.Qh4  Rxh4 }
27. Qd3 Rd5 28. Qf1 Rg5+ 29. Bg3 Bxd6 30. Qg2 Ne4
{ This centralization decides the game. The rest requires no commentary. } 31.
Rxd6 Nxd6 32. Qxc6 Re1+ 33. Kh2 bxc6 34. Bxd6 Rd5 35. Bf4 Rdd1 36. Be3 a6 37.
Bxc5 Rh1+ 38. Kg3 Rdg1+ 39. Kf4 Rxh3 40. a4 Rhh1 41. b4 Rxb1 42. Ra2 Ra1 43.
Rd2 Rhd1 44. Re2 Re1 45. Rd2 Rad1 46. Rb2 Rd5 47. Be3 Ra1 48. a5 Rh1 49. Kg3
Rg1+ 50. Kh2 Rg4 51. Kh3 Re4 52. Kg2 Rd3 53. Bc5 Kf7 54. Rb1 g5 55. Rc1 Kf6 56.
c4 Kf5 57. b5 Rg4+ 58. Kh2 cxb5 59. cxb5 axb5 60. a6 Rc4 61. a7 Rd8 62. Rd1 Ra8
63. Rd5+ Ke4 64. Rxg5 Kf3 65. Rf5+ Rf4 66. Rh5 Rf7 67. Rh3+ Ke4 68. Rb3 Rb7 69.
Rb4+ Kd5 70. Be3 Kc6 71. f4 Raxa7 72. Bxa7 Rxa7 73. Rb1 Rb7 74. Kg3 b4 75. f5
b3 76. Kf4 Kd5 77. Kg5 b2 78. f6 Ke6 79. Re1+ Kf7 80. Rb1 Rb5+ 81. Kh6 Kxf6 82.
Kxh7 Ke5
{ A very convincing and instructive game by the super talented Hungarian GM. }
