[Black "2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bb5 f5 4.d3 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 f5
{ The Schliemann @@StartBracket@@also known as Jaenisch@@EndBracket@@ Gambit is a bold choice to contest one of the most classical and respected chess openings.   Apart from the fact that this line is sharp and confrontational, it also allows players to reduce their workload by eliminating a large number of side variations, such as the exchange Spanish, the early d4 lines, and the early d3 variations, etc. }
4. d3
{ The most popular choice on club level. This move, however, is a tad too timid and passive to be a serious attempt at refuting the Schliemann. }
4... fxe4 { This capture is actually a must as exf5 was a threat! } 5. dxe4 Nf6
6. O-O Bc5
{ This move introduces one of the important themes in the Schliemann: Black happily parts with a pawn @@StartBracket@@or two!@@EndBracket@@ in order to obtain the Bishop pair and some initiative! }
7. Bxc6
{ Is the most challenging response, after which the game becomes very sharp. }
7... bxc6 8. Nxe5 O-O 9. Nc3 d6
{ This move encourages White to grab another pawn on c6, but this comes at a cost! }
10. Na4 { Is the toughest challenge in this variation. } 10... Qe8 11. Nd3 Bg4
{ Since we are a pawn down, it is important to keep on annoying White every step of the way! }
12. Qe1 Bd4 { This move provokes c3, which weakens the light-colored complex. }
13. c3 Bb6 14. Nxb6 axb6 15. f3 Be6
{ Another annoying move, as it forces further weaknesses. } 16. a3 Bc4 17. Qd1
Qg6
{ And despite the material deficit, Black has enough play on the light squares to keep the balance.   Note that White's only winning ambition is based on either an f3-f4 or an e4-e5 push, and neither one is realistic. }
