1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 f5
{ The Schliemann @@StartBracket@@also known as Jaenisch@@EndBracket@@ Gambit is a bold choice to contest one of the most classical and respected chess openings.   Apart from the fact that this line is sharp and confrontational, it also allows players to reduce their workload by eliminating a large number of side variations, such as the exchange Spanish, the early d4 lines, and the early d3 variations, etc. }
4. exf5
{ This capture is not good here, as Black gets a tempo with the e5-e4 push. This is the feature of this opening that makes it a successful 'reversed Kings Gambit'. }
4... e4 5. Qe2 Qe7 6. Bxc6
{ A very unfortunate trade that needs to be played in order to secure the d4 square for the Knight. }
6... bxc6 7. Nd4 Nf6 8. O-O Qe5
{ Attacking the d4 Knight but also pressuring the f5 pawn. } 9. c3 Bd6 10. g3
a5
{ And the subsequent Ba6-d3 maneuver is going to paralyze the entire white queenside. }
