[Black "2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bb5 f5 4.Nc3 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 f5
{ The Schliemann @@StartBracket@@also known as Jaenisch@@EndBracket@@ Gambit is a bold choice to contest one of the most classical and respected chess openings.   Apart from the fact that this line is sharp and confrontational, it also allows players to reduce their workload by eliminating a large number of side variations, such as the exchange Spanish, the early d4 lines, and the early d3 variations, etc. }
4. Nc3 fxe4 5. Nxe4 Nf6 6. Qe2 d5 7. Nxf6+ gxf6
{ 7...Qxf6?  is not a good way to sac a pawn, because of  8.Qxe5+ } 8. d4 Bg7
{ This is the right way to sac!   Once again, our priority is piece activity and initiative! }
9. dxe5 O-O 10. e6
{ White uses a clever positional countermeasure: Instead of grabbing a free pawn, the idea is to mess with our structure and the activity of our g7 Bishop. }
10... Ne5 { Black needs to round up the e6 pawn. } 11. O-O c6
{ Before we recuperate the material, we solidify the center with a tempo. } 12.
Bd3 Bxe6
{ A curious position has arisen: Black dominates the center and has a superior development.   On the other hand, our structure is very shaky, in particular, the f6 pawn is an eyesore. White's main goal is to plant a piece on f5, whereas we should try our best to frustrate this idea. }
13. Nd4 Bg4 { Forcing f3 before retreating the Bishop. } 14. f3 Bd7 15. Bf5
{ Strangely enough, this small mistake is the most popular move both on top GM and club level! }
15... Re8
{ This move creates an annoying tension between the Rook and the white Queen and also covers the e6 square. }
16. Qf2 c5
{ Black has managed to undermine the blockade and clearly stands better.   Once we secure the c5 pawn with b7-b6 we can liberate the g7 bishop with an f5 push. }
*

