1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 f5
{ The Schliemann @@StartBracket@@also known as Jaenisch@@EndBracket@@ Gambit is a bold choice to contest one of the most classical and respected chess openings.   Apart from the fact that this line is sharp and confrontational, it also allows players to reduce their workload by eliminating a large number of side variations, such as the exchange Spanish, the early d4 lines, and the early d3 variations, etc. }
4. Nc3 fxe4 5. Nxe4 Nf6 6. Nxf6+ Qxf6 7. Qe2
{ White goes after the e5 pawn, which we can't hold any longer due to the additional d2-d4 threat.   This, however, is hardly a problem, as we often sac a pawn in the Schliemann in order to gain the initiative. }
7... Be7 { This move shields the King from unwanted checks along the e-file. }
8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. d4 { Is a dangerous idea that we need to respect! } 9... Qg6
{ As almost always, our favourite response to problems is to sacrifice a pawn and try to grab the initiative! }
10. O-O d6 11. Qc4 { This is by far the best. } 11... d5 12. Qc3 exd4 13. Nxd4
c5
{ Black needs to grab some momentum in order to be able to finish development.   This is the point where Stockfish calms the farm and realizes that White's advantage is nowhere near as large as it seemed a few moves ago... }
14. Nb5 O-O
{ Yep, in case I have not mentioned it already, pawn sacrifices tend to be our bread and butter in this line. }
15. Nxc7 Rb8 16. Nxd5 Bd6
{ The character of the game has changed dramatically: White's initiative has fizzled out, and it is now our turn to do damage with our growing activity! }
17. Qd3
{ 17.Qg3?!  Is well met by:  17...Qe6!   @@StartFEN@@1rb2rk1/p5pp/3b2q1/2pN4/8/6Q1/PPP2PPP/R1B2RK1 b - - 2 17@@EndFEN@@  17...Bxg3??  would have been a blunder, as White is clearly better after  18.Ne7++- }
17... Bf5 18. Qg3 { A cheeky sortie, hoping to sell the Ne7 trick. } 18... Bxc2
{ By regaining one pawn, we more or less restore equality, as the Bishop pair remains super powerful. }
19. Qxg6 Bxg6 20. Re1 Rfd8
{ And this endgame offers no real winning chances for White, as our pressure and activity shall prevail! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12.1) Ruy Lopez Schliemann - Model Games"]
[Black "Chirila, Ioan Cristian vs. Khachiyan, Melikset, ICC 2011"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 f5 4. d3 fxe4 5. dxe4 Nf6 6. Bg5 Bc5 7. O-O d6 8.
Nc3 O-O 9. Nd5 Kh8 10. Nh4
{ White intends to play Bxf6 followed by Qh5.   Once again, it is our duty to demonstrate the fact that the kingside is our playground! }
10... Nd4 { 10...Be6  may be more accurate. } 11. Bc4 b5 12. Bd3 c6 13. Nxf6
gxf6 14. Bh6 Rg8
{ And now we have exactly what we wanted. Our 'damaged' kingside allows us to attack on the kingside, mostly due to the semi-open g-file. }
15. Kh1 f5
{ Black's aggression is admirable, this is what it looks like when the Schliemann is played in the right spirit! }
16. Nxf5 Bxf5 17. exf5 e4
{ The point of the tactical skirmish.   18.Bxe4  would be strongly met by  18...Qh4  highlighting the loose Bishops. }
18. Be2 Nxf5 19. Bf4 Qf6 20. c3 Rxg2
{ A beautiful strike! For a tiny material investment Black cracks the White defense open. }
21. Kxg2 Nh4+ 22. Kh1 Qxf4 23. Bh5 Rf8
{ 23...d5!  Was more accurate, as now Black gets to keep the Queens on the board.  24.Qg4  Qf6∓ }
24. Qg4 Bxf2 25. Qxf4 Rxf4 26. Be8 e3 27. Rae1
{ This blunder makes Black's job super easy. More tenacious would have been   27.Bxc6  a6  28.Rae1  Rc4  29.Bb7  Bxe1  30.Rxe1  When the win is not guaranteed at all. }
27... Nf3 28. Re2 Ne5
{ Black secures the c6 pawn and with it an easy victory. } 29. Rd1 d5 30. Kg2
Rg4+ 31. Kh1 Kg7 32. Rf1 Kh6 33. Rfxf2 exf2 34. Rxf2 Rg8 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12.1) Ruy Lopez Schliemann - Model Games"]
[Black "Renet, Olivier vs. Tseitlin, Mikhail S, Palma de Mallorca 1989"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 f5 4. Nc3 fxe4 5. Nxe4 Nf6 6. Qe2 d5 7. Nxf6+ gxf6
8. d4 Bg7 9. dxe5 O-O 10. e6 Ne5 11. O-O c6 12. Bd3 Bxe6 13. Nd4 Bg4 14. f3 Bd7
15. Nf5
{ As I mentioned in the opening section, this blockade is too soon, and Black can try to exploit White's lagging development now.   15.c3  Is the preferred move by the devil, aka Stockfish. }
15... Nxd3 16. Qxd3 Qb6+ 17. Kh1 Bxf5 18. Qxf5
{ The theme is already known to us from the opening section. Although our g7 Bishop is tragically bad, this is more than compensated by the enormous activity of our heavy pieces. }
18... Rae8 19. Bf4 Re2 20. b3 Rfe8
{ Although technically the position is still equal, it is super unpleasant for White, who must rely on only moves. }
21. h4 { Right away an inaccuracy. Rac1 was necessary. } 21... Qb4 22. Rfd1 Qc5
{ Black is gradually improving his position, while White is frantically trying to keep his position together. }
23. Rd2 { A decisive error under tremendous pressure. } 23... Rxd2 24. Bxd2 Qd4
{ The triple attack decides, the rest is elementary. } 25. Rd1 Qxh4+ 26. Kg1
Re2 27. Qg4 Qf2+ 28. Kh1 f5 29. Qg5 h6
{ A lovely game by Tseitlin, who demonstrated how dangerous the Schliemann can be.   Black fought for the initiative and free-piece play virtually from move 3 and his ambitious style got handsomely rewarded. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12.1) Ruy Lopez Schliemann - Model Games"]
[Black "Ajrapetian, Gevorg vs. Popov, Ivan, Dagomys 2010"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 f5 4. Nc3 fxe4 5. Nxe4 Nf6 6. Nxf6+ Qxf6 7. Qe2 Be7
8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. Nxe5 Qe6 10. d4 O-O
{ Although our variation runs here with Bf6 instead of O-O, I decided to include this game for the wealth of motifs it features. }
11. Qc4 Qxc4 12. Nxc4 Rb8 { 12...Ba6  Seems more logical. } 13. c3 c5
{ As I mentioned in the opening section, in this endgame Black's compensation comes from the power of the line moving pieces.   Both the rooks and the Bishops have immense potential to hurt the undeveloped white army. }
14. d5 Ba6 15. Ne3 Bf6
{ Black's pressure is rapidly building, while White is jumping around with the Knight. Black is already better! }
16. f3 Rfe8 17. Kf2 Bd3 18. g3 c4
{ Stage one is complete, and the white army is virtually paralyzed. } 19. a4 a5
20. Re1 Be7 { This re-routing is going to wreak havoc very soon! } 21. Nd1 Bc5+
22. Be3 Rxe3
{ The sacrifice is very much a standard idea here, the double exclam is more for what is coming afterwards. }
23. Rxe3
{ 23.Nxe3  Rxb2+  24.Kg1  Be2  25.Kf2  Bd1+  26.Kg1  Bxf3  Is terminal. } 23...
Re8 24. Rc1 { White had to stop Bc2. } 24... g5
{ And lo and behold, the entire white army has been paralyzed. White simply has no way to break the bind! }
25. h3 h5 26. f4 g4 27. hxg4 hxg4
{ White has run out of moves and and is now forced to allow the decisive Bc2. }
28. Ra1 Kf7 { Black is not in a hurry, the zugzwang can be recreated at will! }
29. Ra3 Bc2 30. Ke1 Rxe3+ 31. Nxe3 Bxe3 { The rest is simple. } 32. Ra1 Bd3 33.
Kd1 Kf6 34. Ra3 Bc5 35. Ra1 Bf2 36. Kd2 Bxg3 37. b4 Bxf4+ 38. Ke1 axb4 39. cxb4
g3 40. a5 c3 41. a6 Bd2+ { A beautiful endgame by GM Popov! } *

