1. e4 e5 2. d3 { This move usually leads to a reverse Philidor. } 2... Nf6 3.
Nf3 Nc6 4. Nbd2 d5 5. Be2 Bc5
{ And indeed, we have now a reversed Philidor.   Considering that the regular Philidor is not something I would write home about, the reverse version represents no danger either. }
6. O-O O-O 7. c3 a5 { It is vital to stop White's queenside play with b2-b4. }
8. Qc2 Re8
{ And Black has a comfortable game. Usually, we follow up with h6-Be6-Qd7-Rad8. }
