[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. c3 Nf6 3. d4
{ 3.d3  d5  4.Nd2  Nc6  transposes to the 2. d3 lines. } 3... Nxe4 4. Bd3 d5
{ These positions are largely reminiscent of the Petroff, with the exception that instead of a useful Nf3, White has thrown in a 'lemon' c2-c3 push. }
5. dxe5 Nc6 6. Nf3 Bg4
{ And Black is clearly ahead already as the e5 pawn is very tricky to hang onto for White. }
7. Bf4 f6 8. exf6 Qxf6
{ A rude shock as now  9.Bxc7  loses to  9...Qe7  with a deadly discovered check to follow! }
9. Be3 O-O-O
{ And Black has a commanding lead in development.   We dominate the center and on top of it all, we are threatening with Ne5! }
