1. e4 e5 2. Qh5
{ This move is setting up the classic cheapo with  2...g6??  3.Qxe5+   This is also a way to go for the Scholar's Mate. }
2... Nc6 3. Bc4 g6 4. Qf3
{ White insists on playing kindergarten style, but then again, recently the MAN himself, Magnus Carlsen tried it against GM Dominguez.   Then again, Magnus often likes to play for memes! 😊 }
4... Nf6 { Stopping the mate and developing a new piece. } 5. Ne2 Bg7
{ Having played g6, we might as well utilize the Fianchetto opportunity. } 6.
d3 d6
{ This is where White troubles begin. Since both Bg4 and Nb4 are annoying threats, White must embark on the journey of 'doggy ears'. }
7. h3 Nb4
{ We should not wait for a3 to deny our fun! Note that this move attacks c2 but also supports a central break with d6-d5. }
8. Bb3 Be6 9. Na3 d5
{ And Black is clearly ahead.   We dominate the center and our piece coordination is way superior. White is struggling to complete development meaningfully.   ...O-O followed By ...Qd7 & ... Rad8 looks like the best way to continue. }
